{"title_page": "Darryl Sharpton", "text_new": "{{short description|American football linebacker}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Darryl Sharpton\n|image=\n|caption=\n|number=51, 96, 53\n|position=[[Linebacker]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1988|01|01}}\n|birth_place=[[El Portal, Florida]]\n|height_ft=5\n|height_in=11\n|weight_lbs=235\n|high_school=[[Coral Gables Senior High School|Coral Gables Senior]]<br>([[Coral Gables, Florida]])\n|college=[[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami (FL)]]\n|draftyear=2010\n|draftround=4\n|draftpick=102\n|highlights=\n* Second-team All-[[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] (2009)\n|pastteams=\n* [[Houston Texans]] ({{NFL Year|2010}}\u2212{{NFL Year|2013}})\n* [[Washington Redskins]] ({{NFL Year|2014}})\n* [[Chicago Bears]] ({{NFL Year|2014}})\n*[[Arizona Cardinals]] ({{NFL Year|2015}})*\n|pastteamsnote = yes\n|status=\n|statweek=\n|statseason=\n|statlabel1=[[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]]\n|statvalue1=176\n|statlabel2=[[Quarterback sack|Sacks]]\n|statvalue2=1.0\n|statlabel3=[[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n|statvalue3=1\n|statlabel4=[[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n|statvalue4=1\n|statlabel5=[[Interceptions]]\n|statvalue5=1\n|nfl=SHA507578\n}}\n'''Darryl Sharpton''' (born January 1, 1988) is a former [[American football]] [[linebacker]]. He was drafted by the [[Houston Texans]] in the fourth round of the [[2010 NFL Draft]]. He played [[college football]] at the [[University of Miami]].\n\n==Early years==\nSharpton attended [[Coral Gables High School]]. As a senior, he recorded 96 [[Tackle (football move)|tackles]], two [[interceptions]], and blocked four [[Punt (gridiron football)|punts]]. As a junior, he had 110 tackles and returned an interception for a [[touchdown]].\n\n==College career==\nAfter being [[redshirted]] as a freshman in 2005, Sharpton earned third-team freshman [[All-America]] by ''[[The Sporting News]]'' and ''[[Collegefootballnews.com]]'' and was selected to The Sporting News [[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] all-freshman team. He finished the season starting five of 12 games recording 41 tackles and a sack. As a sophomore in 2007 he started five of 11 games, recording 57 tackles. As a junior in 2008 recorded 58 tackles and a sack. As a senior in 2009 he had 106 tackles including 8.5 TFL and returned an interception for a touchdown. He also had a forced fumble.\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Houston Texans===\nSharpton was drafted by the [[Houston Texans]] in the fourth round (102nd pick) of the [[2010 NFL Draft]].\n\n===Washington Redskins===\nSharpton signed a one-year contract with the [[Washington Redskins]] on March 13, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|work=WashingtonTimes.com |url=http://washingtontimes.csnwashington.com/news/2014/mar/13/tracy-porter-jason-hatcher-darryl-sharpton-set-joi/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140314155227/http://washingtontimes.csnwashington.com/news/2014/mar/13/tracy-porter-jason-hatcher-darryl-sharpton-set-joi/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 14, 2014 |title=Redskins get rolling by adding defensive starters |date=March 13, 2014 |last=Boyer |first=Zac |accessdate=2014-03-14 }}</ref> The Redskins placed him on [[injured reserve]] on August 30, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|work=WashingtonPost.com|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/football-insider/wp/2014/08/30/phillip-thomas-chase-minnifield-among-defensive-players-cut/|title=Phillip Thomas, Chase Minnifield among defensive players cut|first=Mike|last=Jones|date=August 30, 2014|accessdate=2014-08-30}}</ref> The Redskins terminated Sharpton's contract on September 22.<ref>{{cite web|work=Redskins.com|url=http://www.redskins.com/news-and-events/article-1/DeAngelo-Hall-Out-For-Year-With-Ruptured-Achilles/0af466c3-0f3c-4ae1-a0e2-9aed757eed9f|title=DeAngelo Hall Out For Year With Ruptured Achilles|first=Andrew|last=Walker|date=September 22, 2014|accessdate=2014-09-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924033800/http://www.redskins.com/news-and-events/article-1/DeAngelo-Hall-Out-For-Year-With-Ruptured-Achilles/0af466c3-0f3c-4ae1-a0e2-9aed757eed9f|archive-date=2014-09-24|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Chicago Bears===\nHe signed with the [[Chicago Bears]] on September 24, 2014.<ref>http://www.rotoworld.com/player/nfl/5893/darryl-sharpton</ref>\n\n===Arizona Cardinals===\nSharpton signed with the [[Arizona Cardinals]] in May 2015. On August 19, he was released by the Cardinals.\n\n==Personal life==\nSharpton is the [[Cousin#Basic Definitions|second cousin]] of famous minister [[Al Sharpton]],<ref>{{cite web|work=Redskins.com|url=http://blog.redskins.com/2014/03/14/darryl-sharpton-from-linebacker-u/|title=Darryl Sharpton From Linebacker \u2018U\u2019|first=Gabe|last=Hiatt|date=March 14, 2014|accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref> though by his own admission, he thinks of him more as an uncle.  Sharpton and his wife Jessica are the founders of a furniture store called Edloe Finch based in Houston, Texas.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140315214050/http://www.redskins.com/team/roster/Darryl-Sharpton/17b61b9a-698a-4b8a-8835-17b5906cef87 Washington Redskins bio]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101023023636/http://www.houstontexans.com/team/roster/darryl-sharpton/27f0011d-b08b-400c-95d0-9939627522a4/ Houston Texans bio]\n*[http://www.hurricanesports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=28700&ATCLID=205558391 Miami Hurricanes bio]\n\n{{Texans2010DraftPicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shapton, Darryl}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:Arizona Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Bears players]]\n[[Category:Houston Texans players]]\n[[Category:Miami Hurricanes football players]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Florida]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Coral Gables, Florida]]\n[[Category:Washington Redskins players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football linebacker}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Darryl Sharpton\n|image=\n|caption=\n|number=51, 96, 53\n|position=[[Linebacker]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1988|01|01}}\n|birth_place=[[El Portal, Florida]]\n|height_ft=5\n|height_in=11\n|weight_lbs=235\n|high_school=[[Coral Gables Senior High School|Coral Gables Senior]]<br>([[Coral Gables, Florida]])\n|college=[[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami (FL)]]\n|draftyear=2010\n|draftround=4\n|draftpick=102\n|highlights=\n* Second-team All-[[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] (2009)\n|pastteams=\n* [[Houston Texans]] ({{NFL Year|2010}}\u2212{{NFL Year|2013}})\n* [[Washington Redskins]] ({{NFL Year|2014}})\n* [[Chicago Bears]] ({{NFL Year|2014}})\n*[[Arizona Cardinals]] ({{NFL Year|2015}})*\n|pastteamsnote = yes\n|status=\n|statweek=\n|statseason=\n|statlabel1=[[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]]\n|statvalue1=176\n|statlabel2=[[Quarterback sack|Sacks]]\n|statvalue2=1.0\n|statlabel3=[[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n|statvalue3=1\n|statlabel4=[[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n|statvalue4=1\n|statlabel5=[[Interceptions]]\n|statvalue5=1\n|nfl=SHA507578\n}}\n'''Darryl Sharpton''' (born January 1, 1988) is a former [[American football]] [[linebacker]]. He was drafted by the [[Houston Texans]] in the fourth round of the [[2010 NFL Draft]]. He played [[college football]] at the [[University of Miami]].\n\n==Early years==\nSharpton attended [[Coral Gables High School]]. As a senior, he recorded 96 [[Tackle (football move)|tackles]], two [[interceptions]], and blocked four [[Punt (gridiron football)|punts]]. As a junior, he had 110 tackles and returned an interception for a [[touchdown]].\n\n==College career==\nAfter being [[redshirted]] as a freshman in 2005, Sharpton earned third-team freshman [[All-America]] by ''[[The Sporting News]]'' and ''[[Collegefootballnews.com]]'' and was selected to The Sporting News [[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] all-freshman team. He finished the season starting five of 12 games recording 41 tackles and a sack. As a sophomore in 2007 he started five of 11 games, recording 57 tackles. As a junior in 2008 recorded 58 tackles and a sack. As a senior in 2009 he had 106 tackles including 8.5 TFL and returned an interception for a touchdown. He also had a forced fumble.\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Houston Texans===\nSharpton was drafted by the [[Houston Texans]] in the fourth round (102nd pick) of the [[2010 NFL Draft]].\n\n===Washington Redskins===\nSharpton signed a one-year contract with the [[Washington Redskins]] on March 13, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|work=WashingtonTimes.com |url=http://washingtontimes.csnwashington.com/news/2014/mar/13/tracy-porter-jason-hatcher-darryl-sharpton-set-joi/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140314155227/http://washingtontimes.csnwashington.com/news/2014/mar/13/tracy-porter-jason-hatcher-darryl-sharpton-set-joi/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 14, 2014 |title=Redskins get rolling by adding defensive starters |date=March 13, 2014 |last=Boyer |first=Zac |accessdate=2014-03-14 }}</ref> The Redskins placed him on [[injured reserve]] on August 30, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|work=WashingtonPost.com|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/football-insider/wp/2014/08/30/phillip-thomas-chase-minnifield-among-defensive-players-cut/|title=Phillip Thomas, Chase Minnifield among defensive players cut|first=Mike|last=Jones|date=August 30, 2014|accessdate=2014-08-30}}</ref> The Redskins terminated Sharpton's contract on September 22.<ref>{{cite web|work=Redskins.com|url=http://www.redskins.com/news-and-events/article-1/DeAngelo-Hall-Out-For-Year-With-Ruptured-Achilles/0af466c3-0f3c-4ae1-a0e2-9aed757eed9f|title=DeAngelo Hall Out For Year With Ruptured Achilles|first=Andrew|last=Walker|date=September 22, 2014|accessdate=2014-09-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924033800/http://www.redskins.com/news-and-events/article-1/DeAngelo-Hall-Out-For-Year-With-Ruptured-Achilles/0af466c3-0f3c-4ae1-a0e2-9aed757eed9f|archive-date=2014-09-24|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Chicago Bears===\nHe signed with the [[Chicago Bears]] on September 24, 2014.<ref>http://www.rotoworld.com/player/nfl/5893/darryl-sharpton</ref>\n\n===Arizona Cardinals===\nSharpton signed with the [[Arizona Cardinals]] in May 2015. On August 19, he was released by the Cardinals.\n\n==Personal life==\nSharpton is the [[Cousin#Basic Definitions|second cousin]] of famous minister [[Al Sharpton]],<ref>{{cite web|work=Redskins.com|url=http://blog.redskins.com/2014/03/14/darryl-sharpton-from-linebacker-u/|title=Darryl Sharpton From Linebacker \u2018U\u2019|first=Gabe|last=Hiatt|date=March 14, 2014|accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref> though by his own admission, he thinks of him more as an uncle.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140315214050/http://www.redskins.com/team/roster/Darryl-Sharpton/17b61b9a-698a-4b8a-8835-17b5906cef87 Washington Redskins bio]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101023023636/http://www.houstontexans.com/team/roster/darryl-sharpton/27f0011d-b08b-400c-95d0-9939627522a4/ Houston Texans bio]\n*[http://www.hurricanesports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=28700&ATCLID=205558391 Miami Hurricanes bio]\n\n{{Texans2010DraftPicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shapton, Darryl}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:Arizona Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Bears players]]\n[[Category:Houston Texans players]]\n[[Category:Miami Hurricanes football players]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Florida]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Coral Gables, Florida]]\n[[Category:Washington Redskins players]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1702:300:9ae0:a1db:181b:3a1d:9b25", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Darryl_Sharpton"}
{"title_page": "Ayanna Pressley", "text_new": "{{short description|U.S. Representative from Massachusetts}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Ayanna Pressley\n| image = Ayanna Pressley Portrait.jpg\n| state = [[Massachusetts]]\n| district = {{ushr|MA|7|7th}}\n| term_start = January 3, 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Mike Capuano]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = Member of the [[Boston City Council]]<br>for the at-large district\n| term_start1 = January 4, 2010\n| term_end1 = January 3, 2019\n| predecessor1 = [[Sam Yoon]]\n| successor1 = [[Althea Garrison]]\n| birth_name = Ayanna Soyini Pressley\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1974|2|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Conan Harris|2014}}\n| children = 1 stepdaughter\n| education = [[Boston University]]\n| website = {{url|pressley.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Ayanna Soyini Pressley''' (born February 3, 1974) is an American politician serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[Massachusetts's 7th congressional district]] since 2019. Her district includes the northern three-fourths of [[Boston]], most of [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], parts of [[Milton, Massachusetts|Milton]], as well as all of [[Chelsea, Massachusetts|Chelsea]], [[Everett, Massachusetts|Everett]], [[Randolph, Massachusetts|Randolph]], and [[Somerville, Massachusetts|Somerville]].<ref>Nik DeCosta-Klipa, [https://www.boston.com/news/politics/2018/11/21/ayanna-pressley-photos-first-week-washington-dc Here's what Ayanna Pressley's first week in Washington looked like] Boston.com</ref> One of the lowest IQs in Congress.\n\nA member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], Pressley defeated ten-term incumbent [[Mike Capuano]] in the [[2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Massachusetts#District 7|primary election]] and ran unopposed in the [[2018 Massachusetts general election|general election]]. She was previously elected as an at-large member of the [[Boston City Council]] in 2010. Pressley was the first [[Black women|black woman]] elected to the Boston City Council.\n\nShe is the first black woman elected to Congress from Massachusetts.<ref name=CityOfBoston-Profile-2018>{{cite web|title=City Council: Ayanna Pressley, At-Large|url=https://www.boston.gov/departments/city-council/ayanna-pressley|website=[[City of Boston]]|accessdate=July 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/news/politics/2018/11/06/ayanna-pressley-is-officially-massachusetts-first-black-congresswoman |title=Ayanna Pressley is officially Massachusetts' first black congresswoman |first=William J. |last=Kole |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=November 6, 2018 |accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nPressley was born in [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]],<ref>{{cite web| title= Meet Ayana Pressley, Serving the 7th District of Massachusetts| url= https://pressley.house.gov/about | publisher= US House of Representatives|  website= house.gov | date=| accessdate=July 14, 2019}}</ref> but raised in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], the only child of mother Sandra Pressley (n\u00e9e Echols),<ref name=BostonGlobe-Mother-Obit-2011>{{cite news|last1=Willis|first1=Laurie D.|title=Sandra Pressley, 63; was mother of city councilor|url=http://archive.boston.com/bostonglobe/obituaries/articles/2011/07/14/sandra_pressley_63_was_mother_of_city_councilor/?page=full|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=July 14, 2011}}</ref> who worked multiple jobs to support the family and also worked as a community organizer for the [[Chicago Urban League]] advocating for tenant's rights,<ref name= BostonUCGS-Profile-2009>{{cite news| title=Ayanna Pressley, CGS, will be the first African-American woman ever and the first black candidate in nearly 20 years to serve as a citywide councilor in Boston |url= http://www.bu.edu/cgs/2009/11/04/ayanna-pressley-cgs-ready-to-make-history-is-a-candidate-at-large-for-boston-city-council/|work=[[Boston University College of General Studies]]|date=November 4, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628210457/http://www.bu.edu/cgs/2009/11/04/ayanna-pressley-cgs-ready-to-make-history-is-a-candidate-at-large-for-boston-city-council/| archivedate=June 28, 2011}}</ref> and father Martin Terrell, who struggled with addiction and was incarcerated throughout Pressley's childhood,<ref name=\"Ebbert\">{{cite news |last=Ebbert |first=Stephanie |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/09/05/the-candidate-known-the-amazing-ayanna-pressley/dWw2BGdosGrkb81KD8s5aM/story.html |title=Ayanna Pressley is hailed as a sign of the times |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=September 6, 2018 |accessdate=September 6, 2018 }}</ref> but eventually earned multiple degrees and taught at college level.<ref name=BUToday-CityCouncilRace-2009 /> The marriage ended in divorce.<ref name=BostonGlobe-Mother-Obit-2011 />\n\nPressley grew up on the north side of Chicago<ref name=BUToday-CityCouncilRace-2009>{{cite news|last1=Buccini|first1=Cynthia K.|title=Door to Door, Block by Block|url=http://www.bu.edu/today/2009/door-to-door-block-by-block/|work=BU Today|publisher=[[Boston University]]|date=August 26, 2009|language=en}}</ref> and attended the [[Francis W. Parker School (Chicago)|Francis W. Parker School]].<ref>Katharine Q. Seelye, Astead W. Herndon: [https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/01/us/politics/ayanna-pressley-massachusetts.html ''Ayanna Pressley Seeks Her Political Moment in a Changing Boston.''] In: ''[[The New York Times]]'', September 1, 2018.</ref> While at the prestigious private school, she was a cheerleader, did modeling and [[voice-over]] work, appeared in [[Planned Parenthood]] bus advertisements, and was a [[Debate#Competitive debating|competitive debater]]. During her senior year of high school, she was voted the \"most likely to be mayor of Chicago\" and was the [[commencement speaker]] for her class.<ref name=\"Levenson\" />\n\nHer mother later moved to [[Brooklyn]], where she worked as an executive assistant and later remarried.<ref name=BostonGlobe-Mother-Obit-2011 /> When Pressley was elected to the Boston City Council, her mother would often attend the public meetings, wearing a hat that said \"Mama Pressley.\"<ref name=BostonGlobe-Mother-Obit-2011 />\n\nFrom 1992 to 1994, Pressley attended the [[Boston University College of General Studies|College of General Studies]] at [[Boston University]], but she left school to take a full-time job at the Boston Marriott Copley Place to support her mother, who had lost her job. She took further courses at [[Boston University Metropolitan College]], also known as MET.<ref name=BostonUCGS-Profile-2009 /><ref name=\"Levenson\">{{cite news |last=Levenson |first=Michael |last2=Ebbert |first2=Stephanie |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/09/08/the-life-and-rise-ayanna-pressley/pqdppGFPoZPSEwo3Ko23BJ/story.html |title=The life and rise of Ayanna Pressley |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=September 8, 2018 |accessdate=September 11, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== Earlier political career ==\nAfter leaving Boston University, Pressley worked as a district representative for [[United States Representative|Representative]] [[Joseph P. Kennedy II]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]\u2212[[Massachusetts|MA]]), for whom she had interned during college.<ref name=BostonUCGS-Profile-2009 /> The work included assisting constituents with [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] claims and working with senior citizens, veterans, and people with disabilities. Pressley became Kennedy's scheduler, then worked as constituency director, before becoming the political director and senior aide for Senator Kerry.<ref name=BUToday-CityCouncilRace-2009 />\n\nDuring 2009, Pressley served as [[United States Senator]] [[John Kerry]]'s (D-Mass.) political director.\n\n== Boston City Council ==\nPressley was first elected to the Boston City Council in [[Boston City Council election, 2009|November 2009]]. Upon being sworn in on January 4, 2010, she was the first woman [[Person of color|of color]] to serve in the 100-year history of the Boston City Council.<ref name=CityOfBoston-Profile-2018 /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2010/01/04/menino-sworn-in |title=In Inaugural Address, Menino Vows Fresh Look At Old Problems |date=January 4, 2010 |accessdate=January 11, 2019 |publisher=WBUR News}}</ref> The only woman in a field of 15 candidates, Pressley earned one of four at-large spots on the city's 13-member council with nearly 42,000 votes.<ref name=CityOfBoston-Profile-2018 />\n\nIn her first year as a City Councilor, Pressley formed the Committee on Healthy Women, Families, and Communities, which addresses issues such as domestic violence, child abuse, and human trafficking. She worked collaboratively with community members to develop a comprehensive sexual education and health curriculum and update the expectant and parenting student policy. Both were successfully implemented into [[Boston Public Schools]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Ally Boguhn|url=https://rewire.news/article/2018/08/31/activism-is-no-longer-an-option-could-ayanna-pressley-be-the-next-progressive-upset/ |title='Activism Is No Longer an Option': Could Ayanna Pressley Be the Next Progressive Upset? |publisher=ReWire |date=August 31, 2018 |accessdate=January 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Erin O'Brien, a political science professor at [[University of Massachusetts Boston]], during Pressley's time on the City Council, she did not have the reputation for being controversial or as an outsider.<ref name=\"Krantz2019\">{{cite news |last=Krantz |first=Laura |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/07/16/facing-their-toughest-challenge-members-squad-turned-pressley-for-her-positive-loving-tone/wn8yNlcANqD1kFRcSt0jvL/story.html |title=Facing their toughest challenge, members of 'the Squad' turned to Pressley for her 'positive, loving tone' |work=[[The Boston Globe]]|quote=On the council, Pressley did not have the controversial, outsider reputation she has now earned as part of the Squad. O'Brien said that could be because, as the only woman of color on the council earlier in her career, she did not want to jeopardize her seat. |date=July 16, 2019 |accessdate=July 17, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn the council election of [[Boston City Council election, 2011|November 2011]], Pressley faced a competitive re-election, and finished first among at-large candidates with 37,000 votes. She won 13 of the city's 22 wards and finished second in three others. Pressley won Boston's communities of color and many progressive neighborhoods. In all, Pressley placed first in more than half of Boston's 22 wards.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2011/11/10/hard-work-pays-off-for-pressley-city-council-election/dyPNS3Qf1LqrGsxS32eIuK/story.html | title = Hard work pays off for Pressley in City Council election | accessdate = May 29, 2013 | newspaper = The Boston Globe}}</ref> Pressley topped the ticket again in [[Boston City Council election, 2013|November 2013]] and [[Boston City Council election, 2015|November 2015]], and placed second in [[Boston City Council election, 2017|November 2017]].<ref>{{cite web |title=City Councilor At Large (Ward and Precinct) |url=http://www.cityofboston.gov/images_documents/2013%20-%2011-05-13%20-%20City%20Councillor%20at%20Large%20Ward%20%26%20Precinct%20Results_tcm3-41961.pdf |website=State and City election results {{!}} Boston.gov |publisher=City of Boston |date=November 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=/00:00Playing Live |url=http://www.wbur.org/2013/11/06/women-top-boston-at-large-city-councilor-race |title=Women Top Boston At-Large City Councilor Race &#124; WBUR News |publisher=Wbur.org |date=November 6, 2013 |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/elections/2017/boston/city-council?p1=BG_election_nav_council|title=Boston election results 2017 - Boston city council results - The Boston Globe|first=The Boston|last=Globe|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== U.S. House of Representatives ==\n<!-- does not need a subsection yet as only one election is being discussed -->\n{{Main|2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Massachusetts#District 7}}\nIn January 2018, Pressley announced her challenge to incumbent United States Representative [[Michael Capuano]] in the 2018 Democratic primary nomination for the [[Massachusetts's 7th congressional district]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Joshua|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/01/30/ayanna-pressley-challenge-michael-capuano-primary-for-congress/BxOGmFtBk9uOLFbQO2d9YI/story.html|title=Ayanna Pressley to challenge Michael Capuano in primary for Congress|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> No Republican even filed, meaning that whoever won the primary would be all but assured of victory in November.\n\nThe 7th district is traditionally Democratic and is the state's only district where the majority of residents are not white. Capuano received endorsements from civil rights veteran and U.S. Representative [[John Lewis (civil rights leader)|John Lewis]] of Georgia as well as U.S. Representative [[Maxine Waters]] of California.<ref name=NYTimes-JohnLewis-MaxineWaters-2018>{{cite news|last1=Herndon|first1=Astead W.|title=John Lewis and Other Black Leaders Spurn Black Challenger in Boston|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/19/us/politics/john-lewis-elections-black-caucus.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 19, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nPressley was endorsed by ''[[The Boston Globe]]''<ref>{{cite news|author=<!----> |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/opinion/editorials/2018/08/25/endorsement-democrats-should-choose-ayanna-pressley-for-seventh-district/E5YhYoFCXesjJU2ThByDaK/story.html |title=Endorsement: Democrats should choose Ayanna Pressley for the Seventh District |newspaper=The Boston Globe |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref> and local chapter of the hotel and electrical worker union,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastietimes.com/2018/04/21/political-endorsements/ |title=Political Endorsements &#124; East Boston Times-Free Press |publisher=Eastietimes.com |date=April 21, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref> Grassroots movements including [[Democracy for America]], [[Brand New Congress]] and the [[Justice Democrats]] supported Pressley.<ref>{{cite web|last=Heuser |first=Stephen |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/02/11/democratic-primaries-2018-progressives-402096 |title=Progressives storm Democratic primaries |publisher=Politico |date=February 11, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref> She received the endorsements of former Massachusetts Democratic Party chair [[John E. Walsh]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news/local_coverage/2018/05/ex_mass_democratic_party_chairman_john_walsh_endorses_ayanna_pressley |title=Ex-Mass. Democratic Party chairman John Walsh endorses Ayanna Pressley for Congress |newspaper=Boston Herald |date=May 26, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref> Massachusetts Attorney General [[Maura Healey]],<ref name=\"Ebbert\" /> former [[Newton, Massachusetts|Newton]] mayor [[Setti Warren]]<ref>{{cite news |last=McDonald |first=Danny |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/02/15/setti-warren-endorses-ayanna-pressley-for-congress/o9Pb2IEUlIPuVGRxMjDW2K/story.html |title=Setti Warren endorses Ayanna Pressley for Congress |newspaper=The Boston Globe |date=February 16, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724002302/https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/02/15/setti-warren-endorses-ayanna-pressley-for-congress/o9Pb2IEUlIPuVGRxMjDW2K/story.html |archive-date=July 24, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and Boston city councilor [[Michelle Wu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thebostonsun.com/2018/07/13/ayanna-pressley-for-congress-holds-endorsement-event-with-boston-city-councilor-michelle-wu/ |title=Ayanna Pressley for Congress Holds Endorsement Event with Boston City Councilor Michelle Wu |publisher=The Boston Sun |date=July 13, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref> The nomination win in [[New York's 14th congressional district]] of [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]] over long-time representative [[Joseph Crowley]] increased the visibility of Pressley's campaign.<ref name=\"WaPost-OcasioCortez-Impact-2018\">{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Vanessa|title=After Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez's upset in N.Y., can Ayanna Pressley pull off a repeat in Massachusetts?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2018/06/28/after-alexandria-ocasio-cortezs-upset-in-n-y-can-ayanna-pressley-pull-off-a-repeat-in-massachusetts/|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=June 28, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes-OcasioCortez-Impact-2018\">{{cite news|last1=Seelye|first1=Katharine Q.|last2=Herndon|first2=Astead W.|title=Will a Shocker in New York Have a Ripple Effect in Massachusetts?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/28/us/politics/ocasio-cortez-massachusetts-pressley.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 28, 2018|language=en}}</ref> While some political commentators distinguished Pressley's campaign from that of Ocasio-Cortez in that Capuano was understood to have one of the most progressive records in Congress, the incumbents both represented districts in which the majority of voters are not white.<ref name=\"Intercept-MA7\">{{cite news|last1=Fang|first1=Lee|title=One of the Strongest Progressives in Congress is Facing a Primary Challenger Invoking Identity and Change. Will She Unseat Him?|url=https://theintercept.com/2018/08/18/mike-capuano-ayanna-pressley-massachusetts-primary/|work=[[The Intercept]]|date=August 18, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nLike Capuano, Pressley campaigned as a staunch progressive; indeed, she admitted that her voting record would likely be almost identical to that of Capuano. However, Pressley contended that a reliably liberal voting record was not enough to meet the needs of a district whose demographics and character had changed over the years. She also claimed that the district needed to be represented by someone who would take a more aggressive role in opposing the presidency of [[Donald Trump]]. She campaigned with the slogan \"change can't wait\", and promised that she would bring \"activist leadership.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/04/us/politics/ayanna-pressley-massachusetts.html|title=Ayanna Pressley Upsets Capuano in Massachusetts House Race|author1=Katharine Q. Seelye|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the September 4, 2018, Democratic [[primary election]], Pressley defeated Capuano by a margin of 59% to 41%.<ref>{{cite web |title=Capuano concedes to Pressley in congressional race - The Boston Globe |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2018/09/04/capuano-pressley-count-experience-support-win-primary/BexLGYivjWMnwv4jaYTC1N/story.html |website=BostonGlobe.com |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref> The primary victory was a surprise,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2018/09/04/capuano-pressley-count-experience-support-win-primary/BexLGYivjWMnwv4jaYTC1N/story.html |title='Are you ready to bring change to Washington?' Pressley stuns Capuano on historic night |date= September 4, 2018 |author=Michael Levenson |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> as the last poll before the election showed Capuano with a significant lead, 48% to 35%.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wbur.org/news/2018/08/02/wbur-poll-capuano-pressley-7th-district |title=WBUR Poll: Capuano Maintains 13-Point Lead Over Pressley |date=August 2, 2018 |author=Fred Thys |publisher=[[WBUR]]}}</ref> Part of the reason the polls may have been inaccurate was a surge in the number of primary voters. According to Boston NPR station [[WBUR]], 24 percent of primary voters in the 7th District primary had not voted in the five previous primaries. The percentage of new voters included a disproportionate number of Hispanic and Asian voters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2019/01/04/ayanna-pressley-first-time-voter-file-analysis |title=24 Percent Of 7th District Primary Voters Had Not Voted In Previous 5 Primaries |author=Maeve Duggan |date=January 4, 2019}}</ref> The 7th is so heavily Democratic that any Republican challenger would have faced nearly impossible odds. With a [[Cook Partisan Voting Index]] of D+34, the 7th is by far the most Democratic district in New England. Indeed, the Republicans last put up a challenger in this district during Capuano's first run for it in 1998, when it was numbered as the 8th District. The GOP has only nominated a candidate in this district five times since longtime Speaker [[Tip O'Neill]] retired in 1986. As a result, Pressley won the general election unopposed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/11/06/us/elections/results-massachusetts-elections.html |title=Massachusetts Election Results |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 6, 2018 |accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> \n\n=== Tenure ===\nPressley is the first African American woman elected to represent Massachusetts in Congress.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2018/11/07/ayanna-pressley-officially-massachusetts-black-congresswoman/3RK8xb1hdv7MMoYalZFfMI/story.html |title=Ayanna Pressley officially Massachusetts' 1st black congresswoman |first=William K. |last=Cole |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |url-access=limited |date=November 7, 2018 |accessdate=November 7, 2018 |quote=Republican Senator [[Edward Brooke]] of Massachusetts, who took office in 1967, was the first black politician to be elected by popular vote after the 17th Amendment was ratified in 1913.}}</ref> With the November election victory of [[Jahana Hayes]] in [[Connecticut's 5th congressional district]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.courant.com/politics/elections/hc-election-connecticut-fifth-district-jahana-hayes-20181102-story.html |title=Jahana Hayes Wins, Becomes 1st Black Woman From Connecticut In Congress |first1=Daniela |last1=Altimari |first2=Rebecca |last2=Lurye |newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]] |date=November 6, 2018 |accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref> they are the first women [[Person of color|of color]] to be elected to Congress from [[New England]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Balingit |first1=Moriah |title=She was a teen mother who became teacher of the year. Now, Jahana Hayes wants to become Connecticut's first black Democratic member of Congress |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/education/wp/2018/08/15/she-was-a-teen-mother-who-became-teacher-of-the-year-now-jahana-hayes-wants-to-become-connecticuts-first-black-member-of-congress/ |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Women of Color in Congress |url=http://history.house.gov/Exhibitions-and-Publications/WIC/Historical-Data/Women-of-Color-in-Congress/ |website=History, Art, & Archives |publisher=United States House of Representatives |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPressley is a member of the informal group known as \"[[The Squad (United States Congress)|The Squad]]\", whose members form a unified front to push for progressive changes such as the Green New Deal and Medicare-for-all. The other members of \"The Squad\" are [[Ilhan Omar]] (D-MN), [[Rashida Tlaib]] (D-MI), and [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]] (D-NY) <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/for-ayanna-pressley-the-beauty-of-unexpected-wins-led-to-congress-and-a-historic-office/2019/01/15/61d04b5e-14fc-11e9-b6ad-9cfd62dbb0a8_story.html|title=For Ayanna Pressley, the beauty of unexpected wins led to Congress and a historic office|last=Epstein|first=Kayla|date=January 16, 2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=July 15, 2019}}</ref>. Pressley is the oldest and most politically experienced of the four, who asked her to act as spokesperson after Trump attacked them.<ref name=\"Krantz2019\"/>\n\nIn an interview with The Boston Globe in July 2019, Pressley said her office has received [[death threats]] after president Trump's tweets of July 14, 2019 and in general since her election.<ref>{{cite news |last=Krantz |first=Laura |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2019/07/17/ignoring-president-isn-easy-but-ayanna-pressley-wants-get-back-issues/0jpavQJxtFZpr2N0cmchKO/story.html |title=Ayanna Pressley wants to get back to the issues, although ignoring the president isn't easy |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=July 17, 2019 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718044247/https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2019/07/17/ignoring-president-isn-easy-but-ayanna-pressley-wants-get-back-issues/0jpavQJxtFZpr2N0cmchKO/story.html |archivedate=July 18, 2019 |accessdate=July 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Pressley gave the [[Graduation|commencement]] address to the graduates of University of Massachusetts Boston, saying they are \"President Trump's worst nightmare.\" In her speech she said, \"Represented here today are dreamers and doers, immigrants, people of every race identity, every gender identity and sexuality, sisters rocking Senegalese twists and hijabs.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Kempe |first=Ysabelle |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/05/31/pressley-calls-umass-boston-grads-president-trump-worst-nightmare/tUFyHqiGpUvbIhyr5QarXO/story.html |title=Pressley calls UMass Boston grads 'President Trump's worst nightmare' |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=May 31, 2019 |accessdate=May 31, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOn September 17, 2019, Pressley filed a [[Resolution_(law)#Houses_of_legislature|resolution]] that calls for the House Judiciary Committee to launch [[Impeachment in the United States|impeachment]] proceedings against Supreme Court Justice [[Brett Kavanaugh]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Zhou |first=Li |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/9/17/20870581/ayanna-pressley-brett-kavanaugh-impeachment-resolution |title=Ayanna Pressley just filed an impeachment resolution against Brett Kavanaugh in the House |work=[[Vox (website)]] |date=September 17, 2019 |accessdate=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Pressley introduced a criminal justice reform resolution that calls for decriminalizing consensual [[sex work]], abolishing [[Bail#Bail_bond|cash bail]], [[legalizing marijuana]], abolishing [[capital punishment]], and [[solitary confinement]], and shrinking the U.S. prison population by greater than 80 percent. The house resolution is called The People's Justice Guarantee.<ref>{{cite news |last=Olson |first=Tyler |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/pressley-transgender-inmates-prison |title='Squad' member seeks to ban life sentences, allow transgender inmates to choose their prisons |work=[[Fox News]] |date=November 15, 2019 |accessdate=November 19, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n* [[United States House Committee on Financial Services|'''Committee on Financial Services''']]\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Consumer Protection and Financial Institutions|Subcommittee on Consumer Protection and Financial Institutions]]\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Diversity and Inclusion|Subcommittee on Diversity and Inclusion]]\n* [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Reform|'''Committee on Oversight and Reform''']]\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Economic and Consumer Policy|Subcommittee on Economic and Consumer Policy]]\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Civil Rights and Civil Liberties|Subcommittee on Civil Rights and Civil Liberties]]\n\n=== Caucus memberships ===\n* '''[[Congressional Black Caucus]]'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cbc.house.gov/membership/|title=Congressional Black Caucus|website=cbc.house.gov|language=en|access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''[[Congressional Caucus for Women's Issues]]'''\n* '''[[Congressional Progressive Caucus]]'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cpc-grijalva.house.gov/caucus-members/|title=Congressional Progressive Caucus : Caucus Members|website=cpc-grijalva.house.gov|access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n*Future of Transportation Caucus (Founding Co-Chair)[https://pressley.house.gov/media/press-releases/reps-pressley-garc-takano-launch-future-transportation-caucus]\n\n==Political positions==\n\n==== Donald Trump ====\nDuring her victory speech following the September primary election, Pressley called out President [[Donald Trump]], claiming he is \"a racist, misogynistic, truly empathy-bankrupt man.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Tempera |first=Jacqueline |url=https://www.masslive.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/09/in_historic_upset_boston_city.html |title=Historic upset as Boston City Councilor Ayanna Pressley unseats Rep. Mike Capuano in Massachusetts' 7th Congressional District |work=Mass Live |date=September 5, 2018 |accessdate=September 6, 2018 }}</ref> She supports the [[Impeachment of Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"Markos 2018\">{{cite web | last=Markos | first=Mary | title=Ayanna Pressley puts Donald Trump impeachment on to-do list | website=Boston Herald | date=September 7, 2018 | url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news/us_politics/2018/09/ayanna_pressley_puts_donald_trump_impeachment_on_to_do_list | access-date=September 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Healthcare ====\nPressley is an advocate [[Single-payer healthcare|Medicare for all]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/05/meet-ayanna-pressley-massachusetts-first-black-congresswoman.html|title=Meet Ayanna Pressley, the Democrat who could become Massachusetts' first black Congresswoman|last=Hess|first=Abigail|date=September 5, 2018|work=CNBC|access-date=October 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Pressley and Senator [[Cory Booker]] introduced the Healthy MOMMIES Act, legislation that would expand Medicaid coverage in an attempt to provide comprehensive prenatal, labor, and postpartum care with an extension of the Medicaid pregnancy pathway from 60 days to a full year following birth for the purpose of assuring new mothers have access to services unrelated to pregnancy. The bill also directed Medicaid and the Children's Health Insurance Program's Payment and Access Commission report its data regarding doula care coverage under state Medicaid programs and subsequently develop strategies aimed at improving access to doula care. Pressley said the bill would provide \"a community-based, holistic approach to maternal care that recognizes current disparities in healthcare and critical environmental factors impacting communities.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/442939-booker-ayanna-pressley-introduce-bill-taking-aim-at-black-maternal-death-rates|title=Booker, Ayanna Pressley introduce bill taking aim at black maternal death rates|date=May 9, 2019|publisher=The Hill}}</ref>\n\n==== Civil liberties ====\nPressley supports the [[U.S. national anthem protests (2016\u2013present)|U.S. national anthem protests]], which have been used to bring attention to [[Police brutality in the United States|police brutality]] towards black men and specifically used by athletes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/31/politics/massachusetts-house-primary-ayanna-pressley-mike-capuano/index.html|title=Democrats measure their desire for change in JFK's old district|last1=Bradner|first1=Eric|website=CNN|accessdate=September 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 5, 2019, Pressley proposed lowering the [[Voting rights in the United States#Young people|voting age]] from 18 years old to 16 in an amendment she introduced in Congress. This was her first amendment on the House floor and was intended to amend the [[For the People Act of 2019]]. She said during her speech, \"Young people are the forefront at some of our most existential crises. The time has come. Our young people deserve to have the opportunity to exercise their right to vote.\" Her amendment was defeated 305\u2013126\u20132, with a slight majority of the Democrats and one Republican voting in favor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/ayanna-pressley-lower-voting-age_n_5c8014b0e4b020b54d8194fd|title=Rep. Ayanna Pressley Wants To Lower The Voting Age To 16|last=Ruiz-Grossman|first=Sarah|date=March 6, 2019|work=[[HuffPost]]|accessdate=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn December 5, 2019, Pressley, Senator Booker, and Representatives [[Cedric Richmond]], [[Marcia Fudge]], and [[Barbara Lee]] introduced the Create a Respectful and Open World for Natural Hair (CROWN) Act to ban discrimination based on hair textures and hairstyles that are commonly associated with a particular race or national origin.<ref>[https://pressley.house.gov/media/press-releases/rep-pressley-senator-booker-colleagues-unveil-crown-act-ban-hair-discrimination Rep. Pressley, Senator Booker, Colleagues Unveil CROWN Act to Ban Hair Discrimination] U.S. Congresswoman Ayanna Pressley, retrieved 17 Jan 2020</ref>\n\n==== Immigration ====\nIn June 2018, Pressley called for the defunding of [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]], saying the law enforcement agency poses an \"existential threat\" to immigrant communities.<ref>{{cite news |last=Levenson |first=Michael |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/06/25/ayanna-pressley-endorses-defunding-ice/xMosceaeZ5PYhEi4xqWnMI/story.html |title=Ayanna Pressley endorses defunding ICE |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=June 25, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018 }}</ref> In June 2019, Pressley was one of four Democratic representatives to vote against the Emergency Supplemental Appropriations for Humanitarian Assistance and Security at the Southern Border Act (H.R. 3401, a $4.5 billion border funding bill sponsored by [[Nita Lowey]] that required Customs and Border Protection enact health standards for individuals in custody such as forming standards for individuals for \"medical emergencies; nutrition, hygiene, and facilities; and personnel training.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/450215-house-passes-45b-border-funding-bill|title=House passes $4.5B border funding bill|date=June 25, 2019|publisher=The Hill}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/450363-the-4-house-democrats-who-voted-against-the-border-funding-bill|title=The four House Democrats who voted against the border funding bill|date=June 25, 2019|publisher=The Hill}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/3401|title=H.R.3401 - 116th Congress (2019-2020): Emergency Supplemental Appropriations for Humanitarian Assistance and Security at the Southern Border Act, 2019|last=Lowey|first=Nita M.|date=2019-07-01|website=www.congress.gov|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\n==== Sexual violence and sex work ====\nAs a survivor of sexual violence herself, Pressley states that she would make ending sexual violence a major priority of her work in Congress. Speaking in an article that appeared in ''[[The Nation]]'' she said, \"I have dedicated my life to combating trauma in all forms\u2014domestic, sexual, gun violence\u2014and so the opportunity to potentially be in Congress at a moment of elevated consciousness to codify activism in policy change is certainly an exciting prospect.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Way |first1=Katie |title=What Happens When Political Candidates Say #MeToo |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/happens-political-candidates-say-metoo/ |website=The Nation |accessdate=September 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPressley supports [[decriminalizing sex work]] and prostitution saying, \"Decriminalizing sex work would improve the health and safety of sex workers and put them on the path to greater stability.\" She argued that sex work is the only work available to some [[Social exclusion|marginalized people]], especially [[transgender women]] of color, and that they would be less at risk if they could self advocate and report unlawful acts committed against them.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/12/16/sex-work-sexual-abuse-representative-pressley-activists-debate-decriminalizing-prostitution/zoFBY5SrFH4GuNyzNz2l3H/story.html|title=Sex work or sexual abuse? US Representative Pressley, activists debate decriminalizing prostitution|last=Ebbert|first=Stephanie|date=December 16, 2019|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Labor ====\nOn April 9, 2019, Pressley was one of four House Democrats to introduce the Be HEARD Act, legislation intended to abolish the tipped minimum wage along with ending mandatory arbitration and pre-employment nondisclosure agreements. The bill would also give workers additional time to report harassment and was said by co-sponsor [[Patty Murray]] to come at a time when too many workers are \"still silenced by mandatory disclosure agreements that prevent them from discussing sexual harassment and longstanding practices like the tipped wages that keep workers in certain industries especially vulnerable.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/438051-dems-introduce-sexual-harassment-prevention-bill|title=Dems unveil anti-workplace harassment bill|date=April 9, 2019|first=Rachel|last=Frazin|newspaper=The Hill}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aclu.org/blog/womens-rights/womens-rights-workplace/be-heard-act-will-overhaul-workplace-harassment-laws|title=The BE HEARD Act Will Overhaul Workplace Harassment Laws|website=American Civil Liberties Union|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\n==== Foreign policy ====\nOn July 23, 2019, Pressley voted in favor of [https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-resolution/246 H. Res. 246], a House Resolution introduced by Illinois Congressman [[Brad Schneider]] that formally condemns the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions|Boycott, Divestment, and Sanctions]] movement against [[Israel]]. The resolution passed 398\u201317, and Pressley was noted as the only member of [[The Squad (United States Congress)|\"the Squad\"]] to vote in favor of it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-resolution/246|title=H.Res.246 - 116th Congress (2019-2020): Opposing efforts to delegitimize the State of Israel and the Global Boycott, Divestment, and Sanctions Movement targeting Israel.|last=Schneider|first=Bradley Scott|date=July 23, 2019|website=www.congress.gov|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/23/us/politics/house-israel-boycott-bds.html|title=House Overwhelmingly Condemns Movement to Boycott Israel|last=Stolberg|first=Sheryl Gay|date=2019-07-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/454596-pressley-defends-breaking-with-squad-on-bds-vote|title=Pressley defends breaking with 'squad' on BDS vote|last=Budryk|first=Zack|date=2019-07-24|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\nSpeaking at a fundraiser with [[Ilhan Omar]] in [[Somerville, Massachusetts]], Pressley condemned the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike]] that killed Iranian general [[Qasem Soleimani]], saying, \"It is consistent with the impulsive, reckless, short-sighted foreign policy of the occupant of this White House who I think proceeds as if he's engaging in a game of Battleship and does not prioritize diplomacy.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2020/01/12/pressley-condemns-reckless-short-sighted-attacks-on-iran/|title=Pressley condemns 'reckless, short-sighted' attacks on Iran|date=2020-01-13|website=Boston Herald|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> On [[Twitter]], Pressley had previously voiced her dismay with [[Donald Trump]]'s decision to withdraw from the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action]] (commonly referred to as the \"Iran nuclear deal\").<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ayannapressley/status/993921706598289408|title=President Trump's decision to withdraw from the #IranDeal is irresponsible and shortsighted. Absent a viable alternative, the agreement continues to represent the best option for avoiding a nuclear-armed Iran....|last=Pressley|first=Ayanna|date=2018-05-08|website=@ayannapressley|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\n===2020 Presidential primaries===\nIn November, 2019, Pressley endorsed Senator Elizabeth Warren for president.<ref name=\"Warren\"> {{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/06/us/politics/ayanna-pressley-endorses-elizabeth-warren.html |title=Ayanna Pressley Endorses Elizabeth Warren for President |last=Herndon |first=Astead W |work=NY Times |quote=Ms. Pressley was not a part of the initial round of home-state endorsements during Ms. Warren's campaign launch earlier this year, leading to speculation that she would sit out the presidential primary or back Ms. Harris, the 2020 race's only black woman. Instead, Ms. Pressley joined Ms. Warren's cause, politically cementing the informal friendship that has existed among them for years. |date=November 6, 2019 |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Pressley, who was named one of Warren's three national co-chairs, became a prominent surrogate on the campaign circuit.<ref name=\"WBUR_Warren\"> {{Cite web |url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2020/03/05/elizabeth-warren-sexism-drops-out-campaign |title=Warren Promises To Talk Sexism Later, But Others Aren't Waiting |last=Atkins |first=Kimberly |work=WBUR |quote=One of Warren's most visible surrogates on the campaign trail \u2014 from Boston to South Carolina to Iowa \u2014 was Rep. Ayanna Pressley, who endorsed Warren early on despite the other members of the so-called \"Squad\" of progressive congresswomen of color backing Vermont Sen. Bernie Sanders. |date=March 5, 2020 |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> After Warren's withdrawal, Pressley did not transfer her support to Biden or Sanders.<ref name=\"Politico0306\"> {{Cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/newsletters/massachusetts-playbook/2020/03/06/warren-drops-out-but-does-not-endorse-why-prison-reform-personal-for-pressley-coronavirus-puts-schools-lawmakers-on-alert-488492 |title=Will WARREN ENDORSE \u2014 Why PRISON reform is personal for PRESSLEY \u2014 CORONAVIRUS puts schools, lawmakers on aler |last=Murray |first=Stephanie |work=Politico |quote=Some of Warren's prominent Massachusetts supporters are following her lead, and did not say yesterday whether they'll back Sanders or Biden. |date=March 6, 2020 |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Honors and awards ==\n* 2012: Aspen-Rodel Fellow in Public Leadership, Class of 2012\n* 2012: Truman National Security Project Partner\n* 2014: Greater Boston Chamber of Commerce, 10 Outstanding Young Leaders\n* 2014: [[Victim Rights Law Center]], Leadership Award\n* 2015: ''[[Boston (magazine)|Boston]]'' magazine, 50 Most Powerful People\n* 2015: [[EMILY's List]], [[Gabrielle Giffords]] Rising Star Award<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/02/19/ayanna-pressley-emilys-list_n_6713746.html | work=Huffington Post | title=EMILY's List To Present 'Rising Star' Award To Boston City Councilwoman Ayanna Pressley | date=February 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bernstein |first1=David S. |title=Why Can't EMILY's List Get Millennial Women To Vote? Plus: Ayanna Pressley Walks On Water |url=http://wgbhnews.org/post/why-cant-emilys-list-get-millennial-women-vote-plus-ayanna-pressley-walks-water |work=[[WGBH-TV|WGBH News]] |date=March 6, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150308031934/http://wgbhnews.org/post/why-cant-emilys-list-get-millennial-women-vote-plus-ayanna-pressley-walks-water |archivedate=March 8, 2015}}</ref>\n* 2016: ''[[The New York Times]]'', 14 Young Democrats to Watch\n* 2018: ''[[Boston (magazine)|Boston]]'' magazine, 100 Most Influential People in Boston, #20<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonmagazine.com/news/2018/04/24/most-influential-people-boston/|title=The 100 Most Influential People in Boston|work=[[Boston Magazine]] |date=April 24, 2018 |accessdate=June 22, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nPressley lives in [[Dorchester, Boston|Dorchester, Massachusetts]] with her husband, Conan Harris,<ref name=BostonGlobe-ConanHarris-2017>{{cite news|last1=Irons|first1=Meghan E.|title=Her husband works for Walsh. Her political ally is challenging him. What's a city councilor to do?|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/02/06/her-husband-works-for-walsh-her-political-ally-challenging-him-what-city-councilor/l9qutFZeoWVIp1o9oDxh9N/story.html|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=February 6, 2017}}</ref> and her stepdaughter.<ref name=CityOfBoston-Profile-2018 /> Pressley rarely discusses her religious beliefs but has mentioned that she is a \"woman of faith\" who \"grew up in the church\".<ref>[https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2016/1/31/1477601/-Chris-Hayes-That-s-one-of-the-best-metaphors-I-ve-heard-in-this-campaign Chris Hayes: \"That's one of the best metaphors I've heard in this campaign...\"], Daily Kos, February 1, 2016</ref> Pressley does not drive an automobile and has never learned how to drive.<ref>{{cite news |last=Globe |first=Staff |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/01/31/things-about-ayanna-pressley/hJo1s12ZPJFJezn6GO7K3J/story.html |title=7 things about Ayanna Pressley |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=January 31, 2018 |accessdate=September 6, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nPressley has been public about being a child survivor of [[sexual abuse]].<ref name=WBUR-Turner-SexEd-2011>{{cite news|last1=Toness|first1=Bianca V\u00e1zquez|title=Pressley Is A Compelling, But Vulnerable Councilor|url=http://www.wbur.org/news/2011/02/15/pressley-profile|work=[[WBUR-FM]]|date=February 15, 2011|language=en}}</ref> She was also reportedly sexually assaulted while a student at Boston University.<ref name=TheGrio-100List-Profile-2012>{{cite news|title=TheGrio's 100: Ayanna Pressley, first black woman elected to Boston City Council overcomes life full of obstacles|url=https://thegrio.com/2012/01/30/2012-ayanna-pressley/|work=[[The Grio]]|date=January 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Pressley's husband, Conan Harris, resigned from his position as a senior public safety adviser at Boston City Hall to form his own [[consulting firm]], Conan Harris & Associates.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stout |first=Matt |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/02/16/ayanna-pressley-husband-left-city-hall-launch-consulting-firm-just-before-she-entered-congress/uDxhB2RiwOPuPNLU4x1MuK/story.html |title=Ayanna Pressley's husband left City Hall to launch consulting firm just before she entered Congress |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=February 16, 2019 |accessdate=July 10, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Pressley revealed that she had been diagnosed with [[alopecia areata]], resulting in the loss of all of her hair, and saying in a public announcement \"I want to be freed from the secret and the shame that that secret carries with it.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Moulite |first1=Jessica |title=Exclusive: Rep. Ayanna Pressley Reveals Beautiful Bald Head and Discusses Alopecia for the First Time |url=https://theglowup.theroot.com/exclusive-rep-ayanna-pressley-reveals-beautiful-bald-1841039847 |website=The Glow Up |accessdate=January 16, 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin no change | title=Democratic primary results}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = [[Ayanna Pressley]]\n  |votes      = 59,815\n  |percentage = 58.6\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = [[Mike Capuano]] (incumbent)\n  |votes      = 42,252\n  |percentage = 41.4\n  }}\n{{Election box total no change\n  | votes = 102,067\n  | percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change | title=Massachusetts' 7th congressional district, 2018}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = [[Ayanna Pressley]]\n  |votes      = 216,557\n  |percentage = 98.2\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = n/a\n  |candidate  = Write-ins\n  |votes      = 3,852\n  |percentage = 1.8\n  }}\n{{Election box total no change\n  | votes = 220,409\n  | percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no change\n| winner = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of African-American United States Representatives]]\n* [[Women in the United States House of Representatives]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Tempera, Jacqueline (January, 2019). \"[https://www.masslive.com/news/g66l-2019/01/1d9513df302122/what-drives-ayanna-pressley-in.html What drives Ayanna Pressley? Inside the mind and motivations of Massachusetts' first black congresswoman]\"  MassLive.com\n*{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonmagazine.com/news/2013/07/30/candidate-chat-ayanna-pressley/ |title=City Council Candidate Chat: Ayanna Pressley |first=David S. |last=Bernstein |website=[[Boston (magazine)|Boston]] |date=July 30, 2013 }}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/news/politics/2018/12/06/ayanna-pressley-boston-city-council-farewell |title=Ayanna Pressley bids City Council farewell in impassioned speech |first=Christopher |last=Gavin |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=December 6, 2018 |accessdate=December 6, 2018}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Ayanna Pressley|nowrap=yes}}\n* [https://pressley.house.gov/ Congresswoman Ayanna Pressley] official U.S. House site\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [https://ayannapressley.com/ Ayanna Pressley for Congress]\n{{CongLinks|votesmart=122700|congbio=P000617| fec=H8MA07032 | congress=ayanna-pressley/P000617}}\n* [https://www.boston.gov/departments/city-council/ayanna-pressley Ayanna Pressley] at [[City of Boston]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n | before   = [[Mike Capuano]]\n | state    = Massachusetts\n | district = 7\n | start    = January 7, 2019}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Katie Porter]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=397th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Guy Reschenthaler]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{MA-FedRep}}\n{{Current members of the U.S. House of Representatives}}\n{{Members of the U.S. House of Representatives from Massachusetts}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 116th [[United States Congress]] |state=[[Massachusetts]]}}\n{{USCongRep/MA/116}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pressley, Ayanna}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:African-American members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:African-American people in Massachusetts politics]]\n[[Category:African-American women in politics]]\n[[Category:Boston City Council members]]\n[[Category:Boston University alumni]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Female members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Democrats]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Women city councillors in the United States]]\n[[Category:Women in Massachusetts politics]]\n[[Category:People with alopecia universalis]]\n[[Category:Progressivism in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|U.S. Representative from Massachusetts}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Ayanna Pressley\n| image = Ayanna Pressley Portrait.jpg\n| state = [[Massachusetts]]\n| district = {{ushr|MA|7|7th}}\n| term_start = January 3, 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Mike Capuano]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = Member of the [[Boston City Council]]<br>for the at-large district\n| term_start1 = January 4, 2010\n| term_end1 = January 3, 2019\n| predecessor1 = [[Sam Yoon]]\n| successor1 = [[Althea Garrison]]\n| birth_name = Ayanna Soyini Pressley\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1974|2|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Conan Harris|2014}}\n| children = 1 stepdaughter\n| education = [[Boston University]]\n| website = {{url|pressley.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Ayanna Soyini Pressley''' (born February 3, 1974) is an American politician serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[Massachusetts's 7th congressional district]] since 2019. Her district includes the northern three-fourths of [[Boston]], most of [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], parts of [[Milton, Massachusetts|Milton]], as well as all of [[Chelsea, Massachusetts|Chelsea]], [[Everett, Massachusetts|Everett]], [[Randolph, Massachusetts|Randolph]], and [[Somerville, Massachusetts|Somerville]].<ref>Nik DeCosta-Klipa, [https://www.boston.com/news/politics/2018/11/21/ayanna-pressley-photos-first-week-washington-dc Here's what Ayanna Pressley's first week in Washington looked like] Boston.com</ref>\n\nA member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], Pressley defeated ten-term incumbent [[Mike Capuano]] in the [[2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Massachusetts#District 7|primary election]] and ran unopposed in the [[2018 Massachusetts general election|general election]]. She was previously elected as an at-large member of the [[Boston City Council]] in 2010. Pressley was the first [[Black women|black woman]] elected to the Boston City Council.\n\nShe is the first black woman elected to Congress from Massachusetts.<ref name=CityOfBoston-Profile-2018>{{cite web|title=City Council: Ayanna Pressley, At-Large|url=https://www.boston.gov/departments/city-council/ayanna-pressley|website=[[City of Boston]]|accessdate=July 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/news/politics/2018/11/06/ayanna-pressley-is-officially-massachusetts-first-black-congresswoman |title=Ayanna Pressley is officially Massachusetts' first black congresswoman |first=William J. |last=Kole |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=November 6, 2018 |accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nPressley was born in [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]],<ref>{{cite web| title= Meet Ayana Pressley, Serving the 7th District of Massachusetts| url= https://pressley.house.gov/about | publisher= US House of Representatives|  website= house.gov | date=| accessdate=July 14, 2019}}</ref> but raised in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], the only child of mother Sandra Pressley (n\u00e9e Echols),<ref name=BostonGlobe-Mother-Obit-2011>{{cite news|last1=Willis|first1=Laurie D.|title=Sandra Pressley, 63; was mother of city councilor|url=http://archive.boston.com/bostonglobe/obituaries/articles/2011/07/14/sandra_pressley_63_was_mother_of_city_councilor/?page=full|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=July 14, 2011}}</ref> who worked multiple jobs to support the family and also worked as a community organizer for the [[Chicago Urban League]] advocating for tenant's rights,<ref name= BostonUCGS-Profile-2009>{{cite news| title=Ayanna Pressley, CGS, will be the first African-American woman ever and the first black candidate in nearly 20 years to serve as a citywide councilor in Boston |url= http://www.bu.edu/cgs/2009/11/04/ayanna-pressley-cgs-ready-to-make-history-is-a-candidate-at-large-for-boston-city-council/|work=[[Boston University College of General Studies]]|date=November 4, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628210457/http://www.bu.edu/cgs/2009/11/04/ayanna-pressley-cgs-ready-to-make-history-is-a-candidate-at-large-for-boston-city-council/| archivedate=June 28, 2011}}</ref> and father Martin Terrell, who struggled with addiction and was incarcerated throughout Pressley's childhood,<ref name=\"Ebbert\">{{cite news |last=Ebbert |first=Stephanie |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/09/05/the-candidate-known-the-amazing-ayanna-pressley/dWw2BGdosGrkb81KD8s5aM/story.html |title=Ayanna Pressley is hailed as a sign of the times |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=September 6, 2018 |accessdate=September 6, 2018 }}</ref> but eventually earned multiple degrees and taught at college level.<ref name=BUToday-CityCouncilRace-2009 /> The marriage ended in divorce.<ref name=BostonGlobe-Mother-Obit-2011 />\n\nPressley grew up on the north side of Chicago<ref name=BUToday-CityCouncilRace-2009>{{cite news|last1=Buccini|first1=Cynthia K.|title=Door to Door, Block by Block|url=http://www.bu.edu/today/2009/door-to-door-block-by-block/|work=BU Today|publisher=[[Boston University]]|date=August 26, 2009|language=en}}</ref> and attended the [[Francis W. Parker School (Chicago)|Francis W. Parker School]].<ref>Katharine Q. Seelye, Astead W. Herndon: [https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/01/us/politics/ayanna-pressley-massachusetts.html ''Ayanna Pressley Seeks Her Political Moment in a Changing Boston.''] In: ''[[The New York Times]]'', September 1, 2018.</ref> While at the prestigious private school, she was a cheerleader, did modeling and [[voice-over]] work, appeared in [[Planned Parenthood]] bus advertisements, and was a [[Debate#Competitive debating|competitive debater]]. During her senior year of high school, she was voted the \"most likely to be mayor of Chicago\" and was the [[commencement speaker]] for her class.<ref name=\"Levenson\" />\n\nHer mother later moved to [[Brooklyn]], where she worked as an executive assistant and later remarried.<ref name=BostonGlobe-Mother-Obit-2011 /> When Pressley was elected to the Boston City Council, her mother would often attend the public meetings, wearing a hat that said \"Mama Pressley.\"<ref name=BostonGlobe-Mother-Obit-2011 />\n\nFrom 1992 to 1994, Pressley attended the [[Boston University College of General Studies|College of General Studies]] at [[Boston University]], but she left school to take a full-time job at the Boston Marriott Copley Place to support her mother, who had lost her job. She took further courses at [[Boston University Metropolitan College]], also known as MET.<ref name=BostonUCGS-Profile-2009 /><ref name=\"Levenson\">{{cite news |last=Levenson |first=Michael |last2=Ebbert |first2=Stephanie |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/09/08/the-life-and-rise-ayanna-pressley/pqdppGFPoZPSEwo3Ko23BJ/story.html |title=The life and rise of Ayanna Pressley |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=September 8, 2018 |accessdate=September 11, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== Earlier political career ==\nAfter leaving Boston University, Pressley worked as a district representative for [[United States Representative|Representative]] [[Joseph P. Kennedy II]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]\u2212[[Massachusetts|MA]]), for whom she had interned during college.<ref name=BostonUCGS-Profile-2009 /> The work included assisting constituents with [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] claims and working with senior citizens, veterans, and people with disabilities. Pressley became Kennedy's scheduler, then worked as constituency director, before becoming the political director and senior aide for Senator Kerry.<ref name=BUToday-CityCouncilRace-2009 />\n\nDuring 2009, Pressley served as [[United States Senator]] [[John Kerry]]'s (D-Mass.) political director.\n\n== Boston City Council ==\nPressley was first elected to the Boston City Council in [[Boston City Council election, 2009|November 2009]]. Upon being sworn in on January 4, 2010, she was the first woman [[Person of color|of color]] to serve in the 100-year history of the Boston City Council.<ref name=CityOfBoston-Profile-2018 /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2010/01/04/menino-sworn-in |title=In Inaugural Address, Menino Vows Fresh Look At Old Problems |date=January 4, 2010 |accessdate=January 11, 2019 |publisher=WBUR News}}</ref> The only woman in a field of 15 candidates, Pressley earned one of four at-large spots on the city's 13-member council with nearly 42,000 votes.<ref name=CityOfBoston-Profile-2018 />\n\nIn her first year as a City Councilor, Pressley formed the Committee on Healthy Women, Families, and Communities, which addresses issues such as domestic violence, child abuse, and human trafficking. She worked collaboratively with community members to develop a comprehensive sexual education and health curriculum and update the expectant and parenting student policy. Both were successfully implemented into [[Boston Public Schools]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Ally Boguhn|url=https://rewire.news/article/2018/08/31/activism-is-no-longer-an-option-could-ayanna-pressley-be-the-next-progressive-upset/ |title='Activism Is No Longer an Option': Could Ayanna Pressley Be the Next Progressive Upset? |publisher=ReWire |date=August 31, 2018 |accessdate=January 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Erin O'Brien, a political science professor at [[University of Massachusetts Boston]], during Pressley's time on the City Council, she did not have the reputation for being controversial or as an outsider.<ref name=\"Krantz2019\">{{cite news |last=Krantz |first=Laura |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/07/16/facing-their-toughest-challenge-members-squad-turned-pressley-for-her-positive-loving-tone/wn8yNlcANqD1kFRcSt0jvL/story.html |title=Facing their toughest challenge, members of 'the Squad' turned to Pressley for her 'positive, loving tone' |work=[[The Boston Globe]]|quote=On the council, Pressley did not have the controversial, outsider reputation she has now earned as part of the Squad. O'Brien said that could be because, as the only woman of color on the council earlier in her career, she did not want to jeopardize her seat. |date=July 16, 2019 |accessdate=July 17, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn the council election of [[Boston City Council election, 2011|November 2011]], Pressley faced a competitive re-election, and finished first among at-large candidates with 37,000 votes. She won 13 of the city's 22 wards and finished second in three others. Pressley won Boston's communities of color and many progressive neighborhoods. In all, Pressley placed first in more than half of Boston's 22 wards.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2011/11/10/hard-work-pays-off-for-pressley-city-council-election/dyPNS3Qf1LqrGsxS32eIuK/story.html | title = Hard work pays off for Pressley in City Council election | accessdate = May 29, 2013 | newspaper = The Boston Globe}}</ref> Pressley topped the ticket again in [[Boston City Council election, 2013|November 2013]] and [[Boston City Council election, 2015|November 2015]], and placed second in [[Boston City Council election, 2017|November 2017]].<ref>{{cite web |title=City Councilor At Large (Ward and Precinct) |url=http://www.cityofboston.gov/images_documents/2013%20-%2011-05-13%20-%20City%20Councillor%20at%20Large%20Ward%20%26%20Precinct%20Results_tcm3-41961.pdf |website=State and City election results {{!}} Boston.gov |publisher=City of Boston |date=November 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=/00:00Playing Live |url=http://www.wbur.org/2013/11/06/women-top-boston-at-large-city-councilor-race |title=Women Top Boston At-Large City Councilor Race &#124; WBUR News |publisher=Wbur.org |date=November 6, 2013 |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/elections/2017/boston/city-council?p1=BG_election_nav_council|title=Boston election results 2017 - Boston city council results - The Boston Globe|first=The Boston|last=Globe|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== U.S. House of Representatives ==\n<!-- does not need a subsection yet as only one election is being discussed -->\n{{Main|2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Massachusetts#District 7}}\nIn January 2018, Pressley announced her challenge to incumbent United States Representative [[Michael Capuano]] in the 2018 Democratic primary nomination for the [[Massachusetts's 7th congressional district]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Joshua|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/01/30/ayanna-pressley-challenge-michael-capuano-primary-for-congress/BxOGmFtBk9uOLFbQO2d9YI/story.html|title=Ayanna Pressley to challenge Michael Capuano in primary for Congress|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> No Republican even filed, meaning that whoever won the primary would be all but assured of victory in November.\n\nThe 7th district is traditionally Democratic and is the state's only district where the majority of residents are not white. Capuano received endorsements from civil rights veteran and U.S. Representative [[John Lewis (civil rights leader)|John Lewis]] of Georgia as well as U.S. Representative [[Maxine Waters]] of California.<ref name=NYTimes-JohnLewis-MaxineWaters-2018>{{cite news|last1=Herndon|first1=Astead W.|title=John Lewis and Other Black Leaders Spurn Black Challenger in Boston|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/19/us/politics/john-lewis-elections-black-caucus.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 19, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nPressley was endorsed by ''[[The Boston Globe]]''<ref>{{cite news|author=<!----> |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/opinion/editorials/2018/08/25/endorsement-democrats-should-choose-ayanna-pressley-for-seventh-district/E5YhYoFCXesjJU2ThByDaK/story.html |title=Endorsement: Democrats should choose Ayanna Pressley for the Seventh District |newspaper=The Boston Globe |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref> and local chapter of the hotel and electrical worker union,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastietimes.com/2018/04/21/political-endorsements/ |title=Political Endorsements &#124; East Boston Times-Free Press |publisher=Eastietimes.com |date=April 21, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref> Grassroots movements including [[Democracy for America]], [[Brand New Congress]] and the [[Justice Democrats]] supported Pressley.<ref>{{cite web|last=Heuser |first=Stephen |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/02/11/democratic-primaries-2018-progressives-402096 |title=Progressives storm Democratic primaries |publisher=Politico |date=February 11, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref> She received the endorsements of former Massachusetts Democratic Party chair [[John E. Walsh]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news/local_coverage/2018/05/ex_mass_democratic_party_chairman_john_walsh_endorses_ayanna_pressley |title=Ex-Mass. Democratic Party chairman John Walsh endorses Ayanna Pressley for Congress |newspaper=Boston Herald |date=May 26, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref> Massachusetts Attorney General [[Maura Healey]],<ref name=\"Ebbert\" /> former [[Newton, Massachusetts|Newton]] mayor [[Setti Warren]]<ref>{{cite news |last=McDonald |first=Danny |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/02/15/setti-warren-endorses-ayanna-pressley-for-congress/o9Pb2IEUlIPuVGRxMjDW2K/story.html |title=Setti Warren endorses Ayanna Pressley for Congress |newspaper=The Boston Globe |date=February 16, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724002302/https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/02/15/setti-warren-endorses-ayanna-pressley-for-congress/o9Pb2IEUlIPuVGRxMjDW2K/story.html |archive-date=July 24, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and Boston city councilor [[Michelle Wu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thebostonsun.com/2018/07/13/ayanna-pressley-for-congress-holds-endorsement-event-with-boston-city-councilor-michelle-wu/ |title=Ayanna Pressley for Congress Holds Endorsement Event with Boston City Councilor Michelle Wu |publisher=The Boston Sun |date=July 13, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref> The nomination win in [[New York's 14th congressional district]] of [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]] over long-time representative [[Joseph Crowley]] increased the visibility of Pressley's campaign.<ref name=\"WaPost-OcasioCortez-Impact-2018\">{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Vanessa|title=After Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez's upset in N.Y., can Ayanna Pressley pull off a repeat in Massachusetts?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2018/06/28/after-alexandria-ocasio-cortezs-upset-in-n-y-can-ayanna-pressley-pull-off-a-repeat-in-massachusetts/|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=June 28, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes-OcasioCortez-Impact-2018\">{{cite news|last1=Seelye|first1=Katharine Q.|last2=Herndon|first2=Astead W.|title=Will a Shocker in New York Have a Ripple Effect in Massachusetts?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/28/us/politics/ocasio-cortez-massachusetts-pressley.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 28, 2018|language=en}}</ref> While some political commentators distinguished Pressley's campaign from that of Ocasio-Cortez in that Capuano was understood to have one of the most progressive records in Congress, the incumbents both represented districts in which the majority of voters are not white.<ref name=\"Intercept-MA7\">{{cite news|last1=Fang|first1=Lee|title=One of the Strongest Progressives in Congress is Facing a Primary Challenger Invoking Identity and Change. Will She Unseat Him?|url=https://theintercept.com/2018/08/18/mike-capuano-ayanna-pressley-massachusetts-primary/|work=[[The Intercept]]|date=August 18, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nLike Capuano, Pressley campaigned as a staunch progressive; indeed, she admitted that her voting record would likely be almost identical to that of Capuano. However, Pressley contended that a reliably liberal voting record was not enough to meet the needs of a district whose demographics and character had changed over the years. She also claimed that the district needed to be represented by someone who would take a more aggressive role in opposing the presidency of [[Donald Trump]]. She campaigned with the slogan \"change can't wait\", and promised that she would bring \"activist leadership.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/04/us/politics/ayanna-pressley-massachusetts.html|title=Ayanna Pressley Upsets Capuano in Massachusetts House Race|author1=Katharine Q. Seelye|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the September 4, 2018, Democratic [[primary election]], Pressley defeated Capuano by a margin of 59% to 41%.<ref>{{cite web |title=Capuano concedes to Pressley in congressional race - The Boston Globe |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2018/09/04/capuano-pressley-count-experience-support-win-primary/BexLGYivjWMnwv4jaYTC1N/story.html |website=BostonGlobe.com |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref> The primary victory was a surprise,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2018/09/04/capuano-pressley-count-experience-support-win-primary/BexLGYivjWMnwv4jaYTC1N/story.html |title='Are you ready to bring change to Washington?' Pressley stuns Capuano on historic night |date= September 4, 2018 |author=Michael Levenson |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> as the last poll before the election showed Capuano with a significant lead, 48% to 35%.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wbur.org/news/2018/08/02/wbur-poll-capuano-pressley-7th-district |title=WBUR Poll: Capuano Maintains 13-Point Lead Over Pressley |date=August 2, 2018 |author=Fred Thys |publisher=[[WBUR]]}}</ref> Part of the reason the polls may have been inaccurate was a surge in the number of primary voters. According to Boston NPR station [[WBUR]], 24 percent of primary voters in the 7th District primary had not voted in the five previous primaries. The percentage of new voters included a disproportionate number of Hispanic and Asian voters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2019/01/04/ayanna-pressley-first-time-voter-file-analysis |title=24 Percent Of 7th District Primary Voters Had Not Voted In Previous 5 Primaries |author=Maeve Duggan |date=January 4, 2019}}</ref> The 7th is so heavily Democratic that any Republican challenger would have faced nearly impossible odds. With a [[Cook Partisan Voting Index]] of D+34, the 7th is by far the most Democratic district in New England. Indeed, the Republicans last put up a challenger in this district during Capuano's first run for it in 1998, when it was numbered as the 8th District. The GOP has only nominated a candidate in this district five times since longtime Speaker [[Tip O'Neill]] retired in 1986. As a result, Pressley won the general election unopposed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/11/06/us/elections/results-massachusetts-elections.html |title=Massachusetts Election Results |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 6, 2018 |accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> \n\n=== Tenure ===\nPressley is the first African American woman elected to represent Massachusetts in Congress.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2018/11/07/ayanna-pressley-officially-massachusetts-black-congresswoman/3RK8xb1hdv7MMoYalZFfMI/story.html |title=Ayanna Pressley officially Massachusetts' 1st black congresswoman |first=William K. |last=Cole |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |url-access=limited |date=November 7, 2018 |accessdate=November 7, 2018 |quote=Republican Senator [[Edward Brooke]] of Massachusetts, who took office in 1967, was the first black politician to be elected by popular vote after the 17th Amendment was ratified in 1913.}}</ref> With the November election victory of [[Jahana Hayes]] in [[Connecticut's 5th congressional district]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.courant.com/politics/elections/hc-election-connecticut-fifth-district-jahana-hayes-20181102-story.html |title=Jahana Hayes Wins, Becomes 1st Black Woman From Connecticut In Congress |first1=Daniela |last1=Altimari |first2=Rebecca |last2=Lurye |newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]] |date=November 6, 2018 |accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref> they are the first women [[Person of color|of color]] to be elected to Congress from [[New England]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Balingit |first1=Moriah |title=She was a teen mother who became teacher of the year. Now, Jahana Hayes wants to become Connecticut's first black Democratic member of Congress |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/education/wp/2018/08/15/she-was-a-teen-mother-who-became-teacher-of-the-year-now-jahana-hayes-wants-to-become-connecticuts-first-black-member-of-congress/ |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Women of Color in Congress |url=http://history.house.gov/Exhibitions-and-Publications/WIC/Historical-Data/Women-of-Color-in-Congress/ |website=History, Art, & Archives |publisher=United States House of Representatives |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPressley is a member of the informal group known as \"[[The Squad (United States Congress)|The Squad]]\", whose members form a unified front to push for progressive changes such as the Green New Deal and Medicare-for-all. The other members of \"The Squad\" are [[Ilhan Omar]] (D-MN), [[Rashida Tlaib]] (D-MI), and [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]] (D-NY) <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/for-ayanna-pressley-the-beauty-of-unexpected-wins-led-to-congress-and-a-historic-office/2019/01/15/61d04b5e-14fc-11e9-b6ad-9cfd62dbb0a8_story.html|title=For Ayanna Pressley, the beauty of unexpected wins led to Congress and a historic office|last=Epstein|first=Kayla|date=January 16, 2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=July 15, 2019}}</ref>. Pressley is the oldest and most politically experienced of the four, who asked her to act as spokesperson after Trump attacked them.<ref name=\"Krantz2019\"/>\n\nIn an interview with The Boston Globe in July 2019, Pressley said her office has received [[death threats]] after president Trump's tweets of July 14, 2019 and in general since her election.<ref>{{cite news |last=Krantz |first=Laura |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2019/07/17/ignoring-president-isn-easy-but-ayanna-pressley-wants-get-back-issues/0jpavQJxtFZpr2N0cmchKO/story.html |title=Ayanna Pressley wants to get back to the issues, although ignoring the president isn't easy |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=July 17, 2019 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718044247/https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2019/07/17/ignoring-president-isn-easy-but-ayanna-pressley-wants-get-back-issues/0jpavQJxtFZpr2N0cmchKO/story.html |archivedate=July 18, 2019 |accessdate=July 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Pressley gave the [[Graduation|commencement]] address to the graduates of University of Massachusetts Boston, saying they are \"President Trump's worst nightmare.\" In her speech she said, \"Represented here today are dreamers and doers, immigrants, people of every race identity, every gender identity and sexuality, sisters rocking Senegalese twists and hijabs.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Kempe |first=Ysabelle |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/05/31/pressley-calls-umass-boston-grads-president-trump-worst-nightmare/tUFyHqiGpUvbIhyr5QarXO/story.html |title=Pressley calls UMass Boston grads 'President Trump's worst nightmare' |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=May 31, 2019 |accessdate=May 31, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOn September 17, 2019, Pressley filed a [[Resolution_(law)#Houses_of_legislature|resolution]] that calls for the House Judiciary Committee to launch [[Impeachment in the United States|impeachment]] proceedings against Supreme Court Justice [[Brett Kavanaugh]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Zhou |first=Li |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/9/17/20870581/ayanna-pressley-brett-kavanaugh-impeachment-resolution |title=Ayanna Pressley just filed an impeachment resolution against Brett Kavanaugh in the House |work=[[Vox (website)]] |date=September 17, 2019 |accessdate=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Pressley introduced a criminal justice reform resolution that calls for decriminalizing consensual [[sex work]], abolishing [[Bail#Bail_bond|cash bail]], [[legalizing marijuana]], abolishing [[capital punishment]], and [[solitary confinement]], and shrinking the U.S. prison population by greater than 80 percent. The house resolution is called The People's Justice Guarantee.<ref>{{cite news |last=Olson |first=Tyler |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/pressley-transgender-inmates-prison |title='Squad' member seeks to ban life sentences, allow transgender inmates to choose their prisons |work=[[Fox News]] |date=November 15, 2019 |accessdate=November 19, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n* [[United States House Committee on Financial Services|'''Committee on Financial Services''']]\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Consumer Protection and Financial Institutions|Subcommittee on Consumer Protection and Financial Institutions]]\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Diversity and Inclusion|Subcommittee on Diversity and Inclusion]]\n* [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Reform|'''Committee on Oversight and Reform''']]\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Economic and Consumer Policy|Subcommittee on Economic and Consumer Policy]]\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Civil Rights and Civil Liberties|Subcommittee on Civil Rights and Civil Liberties]]\n\n=== Caucus memberships ===\n* '''[[Congressional Black Caucus]]'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cbc.house.gov/membership/|title=Congressional Black Caucus|website=cbc.house.gov|language=en|access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''[[Congressional Caucus for Women's Issues]]'''\n* '''[[Congressional Progressive Caucus]]'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cpc-grijalva.house.gov/caucus-members/|title=Congressional Progressive Caucus : Caucus Members|website=cpc-grijalva.house.gov|access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n*Future of Transportation Caucus (Founding Co-Chair)[https://pressley.house.gov/media/press-releases/reps-pressley-garc-takano-launch-future-transportation-caucus]\n\n==Political positions==\n\n==== Donald Trump ====\nDuring her victory speech following the September primary election, Pressley called out President [[Donald Trump]], claiming he is \"a racist, misogynistic, truly empathy-bankrupt man.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Tempera |first=Jacqueline |url=https://www.masslive.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/09/in_historic_upset_boston_city.html |title=Historic upset as Boston City Councilor Ayanna Pressley unseats Rep. Mike Capuano in Massachusetts' 7th Congressional District |work=Mass Live |date=September 5, 2018 |accessdate=September 6, 2018 }}</ref> She supports the [[Impeachment of Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"Markos 2018\">{{cite web | last=Markos | first=Mary | title=Ayanna Pressley puts Donald Trump impeachment on to-do list | website=Boston Herald | date=September 7, 2018 | url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news/us_politics/2018/09/ayanna_pressley_puts_donald_trump_impeachment_on_to_do_list | access-date=September 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Healthcare ====\nPressley is an advocate [[Single-payer healthcare|Medicare for all]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/05/meet-ayanna-pressley-massachusetts-first-black-congresswoman.html|title=Meet Ayanna Pressley, the Democrat who could become Massachusetts' first black Congresswoman|last=Hess|first=Abigail|date=September 5, 2018|work=CNBC|access-date=October 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Pressley and Senator [[Cory Booker]] introduced the Healthy MOMMIES Act, legislation that would expand Medicaid coverage in an attempt to provide comprehensive prenatal, labor, and postpartum care with an extension of the Medicaid pregnancy pathway from 60 days to a full year following birth for the purpose of assuring new mothers have access to services unrelated to pregnancy. The bill also directed Medicaid and the Children's Health Insurance Program's Payment and Access Commission report its data regarding doula care coverage under state Medicaid programs and subsequently develop strategies aimed at improving access to doula care. Pressley said the bill would provide \"a community-based, holistic approach to maternal care that recognizes current disparities in healthcare and critical environmental factors impacting communities.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/442939-booker-ayanna-pressley-introduce-bill-taking-aim-at-black-maternal-death-rates|title=Booker, Ayanna Pressley introduce bill taking aim at black maternal death rates|date=May 9, 2019|publisher=The Hill}}</ref>\n\n==== Civil liberties ====\nPressley supports the [[U.S. national anthem protests (2016\u2013present)|U.S. national anthem protests]], which have been used to bring attention to [[Police brutality in the United States|police brutality]] towards black men and specifically used by athletes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/31/politics/massachusetts-house-primary-ayanna-pressley-mike-capuano/index.html|title=Democrats measure their desire for change in JFK's old district|last1=Bradner|first1=Eric|website=CNN|accessdate=September 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 5, 2019, Pressley proposed lowering the [[Voting rights in the United States#Young people|voting age]] from 18 years old to 16 in an amendment she introduced in Congress. This was her first amendment on the House floor and was intended to amend the [[For the People Act of 2019]]. She said during her speech, \"Young people are the forefront at some of our most existential crises. The time has come. Our young people deserve to have the opportunity to exercise their right to vote.\" Her amendment was defeated 305\u2013126\u20132, with a slight majority of the Democrats and one Republican voting in favor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/ayanna-pressley-lower-voting-age_n_5c8014b0e4b020b54d8194fd|title=Rep. Ayanna Pressley Wants To Lower The Voting Age To 16|last=Ruiz-Grossman|first=Sarah|date=March 6, 2019|work=[[HuffPost]]|accessdate=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn December 5, 2019, Pressley, Senator Booker, and Representatives [[Cedric Richmond]], [[Marcia Fudge]], and [[Barbara Lee]] introduced the Create a Respectful and Open World for Natural Hair (CROWN) Act to ban discrimination based on hair textures and hairstyles that are commonly associated with a particular race or national origin.<ref>[https://pressley.house.gov/media/press-releases/rep-pressley-senator-booker-colleagues-unveil-crown-act-ban-hair-discrimination Rep. Pressley, Senator Booker, Colleagues Unveil CROWN Act to Ban Hair Discrimination] U.S. Congresswoman Ayanna Pressley, retrieved 17 Jan 2020</ref>\n\n==== Immigration ====\nIn June 2018, Pressley called for the defunding of [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]], saying the law enforcement agency poses an \"existential threat\" to immigrant communities.<ref>{{cite news |last=Levenson |first=Michael |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/06/25/ayanna-pressley-endorses-defunding-ice/xMosceaeZ5PYhEi4xqWnMI/story.html |title=Ayanna Pressley endorses defunding ICE |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=June 25, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018 }}</ref> In June 2019, Pressley was one of four Democratic representatives to vote against the Emergency Supplemental Appropriations for Humanitarian Assistance and Security at the Southern Border Act (H.R. 3401, a $4.5 billion border funding bill sponsored by [[Nita Lowey]] that required Customs and Border Protection enact health standards for individuals in custody such as forming standards for individuals for \"medical emergencies; nutrition, hygiene, and facilities; and personnel training.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/450215-house-passes-45b-border-funding-bill|title=House passes $4.5B border funding bill|date=June 25, 2019|publisher=The Hill}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/450363-the-4-house-democrats-who-voted-against-the-border-funding-bill|title=The four House Democrats who voted against the border funding bill|date=June 25, 2019|publisher=The Hill}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/3401|title=H.R.3401 - 116th Congress (2019-2020): Emergency Supplemental Appropriations for Humanitarian Assistance and Security at the Southern Border Act, 2019|last=Lowey|first=Nita M.|date=2019-07-01|website=www.congress.gov|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\n==== Sexual violence and sex work ====\nAs a survivor of sexual violence herself, Pressley states that she would make ending sexual violence a major priority of her work in Congress. Speaking in an article that appeared in ''[[The Nation]]'' she said, \"I have dedicated my life to combating trauma in all forms\u2014domestic, sexual, gun violence\u2014and so the opportunity to potentially be in Congress at a moment of elevated consciousness to codify activism in policy change is certainly an exciting prospect.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Way |first1=Katie |title=What Happens When Political Candidates Say #MeToo |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/happens-political-candidates-say-metoo/ |website=The Nation |accessdate=September 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPressley supports [[decriminalizing sex work]] and prostitution saying, \"Decriminalizing sex work would improve the health and safety of sex workers and put them on the path to greater stability.\" She argued that sex work is the only work available to some [[Social exclusion|marginalized people]], especially [[transgender women]] of color, and that they would be less at risk if they could self advocate and report unlawful acts committed against them.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/12/16/sex-work-sexual-abuse-representative-pressley-activists-debate-decriminalizing-prostitution/zoFBY5SrFH4GuNyzNz2l3H/story.html|title=Sex work or sexual abuse? US Representative Pressley, activists debate decriminalizing prostitution|last=Ebbert|first=Stephanie|date=December 16, 2019|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Labor ====\nOn April 9, 2019, Pressley was one of four House Democrats to introduce the Be HEARD Act, legislation intended to abolish the tipped minimum wage along with ending mandatory arbitration and pre-employment nondisclosure agreements. The bill would also give workers additional time to report harassment and was said by co-sponsor [[Patty Murray]] to come at a time when too many workers are \"still silenced by mandatory disclosure agreements that prevent them from discussing sexual harassment and longstanding practices like the tipped wages that keep workers in certain industries especially vulnerable.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/438051-dems-introduce-sexual-harassment-prevention-bill|title=Dems unveil anti-workplace harassment bill|date=April 9, 2019|first=Rachel|last=Frazin|newspaper=The Hill}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aclu.org/blog/womens-rights/womens-rights-workplace/be-heard-act-will-overhaul-workplace-harassment-laws|title=The BE HEARD Act Will Overhaul Workplace Harassment Laws|website=American Civil Liberties Union|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\n==== Foreign policy ====\nOn July 23, 2019, Pressley voted in favor of [https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-resolution/246 H. Res. 246], a House Resolution introduced by Illinois Congressman [[Brad Schneider]] that formally condemns the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions|Boycott, Divestment, and Sanctions]] movement against [[Israel]]. The resolution passed 398\u201317, and Pressley was noted as the only member of [[The Squad (United States Congress)|\"the Squad\"]] to vote in favor of it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-resolution/246|title=H.Res.246 - 116th Congress (2019-2020): Opposing efforts to delegitimize the State of Israel and the Global Boycott, Divestment, and Sanctions Movement targeting Israel.|last=Schneider|first=Bradley Scott|date=July 23, 2019|website=www.congress.gov|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/23/us/politics/house-israel-boycott-bds.html|title=House Overwhelmingly Condemns Movement to Boycott Israel|last=Stolberg|first=Sheryl Gay|date=2019-07-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/454596-pressley-defends-breaking-with-squad-on-bds-vote|title=Pressley defends breaking with 'squad' on BDS vote|last=Budryk|first=Zack|date=2019-07-24|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\nSpeaking at a fundraiser with [[Ilhan Omar]] in [[Somerville, Massachusetts]], Pressley condemned the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike]] that killed Iranian general [[Qasem Soleimani]], saying, \"It is consistent with the impulsive, reckless, short-sighted foreign policy of the occupant of this White House who I think proceeds as if he's engaging in a game of Battleship and does not prioritize diplomacy.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2020/01/12/pressley-condemns-reckless-short-sighted-attacks-on-iran/|title=Pressley condemns 'reckless, short-sighted' attacks on Iran|date=2020-01-13|website=Boston Herald|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> On [[Twitter]], Pressley had previously voiced her dismay with [[Donald Trump]]'s decision to withdraw from the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action]] (commonly referred to as the \"Iran nuclear deal\").<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ayannapressley/status/993921706598289408|title=President Trump's decision to withdraw from the #IranDeal is irresponsible and shortsighted. Absent a viable alternative, the agreement continues to represent the best option for avoiding a nuclear-armed Iran....|last=Pressley|first=Ayanna|date=2018-05-08|website=@ayannapressley|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\n===2020 Presidential primaries===\nIn November, 2019, Pressley endorsed Senator Elizabeth Warren for president.<ref name=\"Warren\"> {{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/06/us/politics/ayanna-pressley-endorses-elizabeth-warren.html |title=Ayanna Pressley Endorses Elizabeth Warren for President |last=Herndon |first=Astead W |work=NY Times |quote=Ms. Pressley was not a part of the initial round of home-state endorsements during Ms. Warren's campaign launch earlier this year, leading to speculation that she would sit out the presidential primary or back Ms. Harris, the 2020 race's only black woman. Instead, Ms. Pressley joined Ms. Warren's cause, politically cementing the informal friendship that has existed among them for years. |date=November 6, 2019 |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Pressley, who was named one of Warren's three national co-chairs, became a prominent surrogate on the campaign circuit.<ref name=\"WBUR_Warren\"> {{Cite web |url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2020/03/05/elizabeth-warren-sexism-drops-out-campaign |title=Warren Promises To Talk Sexism Later, But Others Aren't Waiting |last=Atkins |first=Kimberly |work=WBUR |quote=One of Warren's most visible surrogates on the campaign trail \u2014 from Boston to South Carolina to Iowa \u2014 was Rep. Ayanna Pressley, who endorsed Warren early on despite the other members of the so-called \"Squad\" of progressive congresswomen of color backing Vermont Sen. Bernie Sanders. |date=March 5, 2020 |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> After Warren's withdrawal, Pressley did not transfer her support to Biden or Sanders.<ref name=\"Politico0306\"> {{Cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/newsletters/massachusetts-playbook/2020/03/06/warren-drops-out-but-does-not-endorse-why-prison-reform-personal-for-pressley-coronavirus-puts-schools-lawmakers-on-alert-488492 |title=Will WARREN ENDORSE \u2014 Why PRISON reform is personal for PRESSLEY \u2014 CORONAVIRUS puts schools, lawmakers on aler |last=Murray |first=Stephanie |work=Politico |quote=Some of Warren's prominent Massachusetts supporters are following her lead, and did not say yesterday whether they'll back Sanders or Biden. |date=March 6, 2020 |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Honors and awards ==\n* 2012: Aspen-Rodel Fellow in Public Leadership, Class of 2012\n* 2012: Truman National Security Project Partner\n* 2014: Greater Boston Chamber of Commerce, 10 Outstanding Young Leaders\n* 2014: [[Victim Rights Law Center]], Leadership Award\n* 2015: ''[[Boston (magazine)|Boston]]'' magazine, 50 Most Powerful People\n* 2015: [[EMILY's List]], [[Gabrielle Giffords]] Rising Star Award<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/02/19/ayanna-pressley-emilys-list_n_6713746.html | work=Huffington Post | title=EMILY's List To Present 'Rising Star' Award To Boston City Councilwoman Ayanna Pressley | date=February 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bernstein |first1=David S. |title=Why Can't EMILY's List Get Millennial Women To Vote? Plus: Ayanna Pressley Walks On Water |url=http://wgbhnews.org/post/why-cant-emilys-list-get-millennial-women-vote-plus-ayanna-pressley-walks-water |work=[[WGBH-TV|WGBH News]] |date=March 6, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150308031934/http://wgbhnews.org/post/why-cant-emilys-list-get-millennial-women-vote-plus-ayanna-pressley-walks-water |archivedate=March 8, 2015}}</ref>\n* 2016: ''[[The New York Times]]'', 14 Young Democrats to Watch\n* 2018: ''[[Boston (magazine)|Boston]]'' magazine, 100 Most Influential People in Boston, #20<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonmagazine.com/news/2018/04/24/most-influential-people-boston/|title=The 100 Most Influential People in Boston|work=[[Boston Magazine]] |date=April 24, 2018 |accessdate=June 22, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nPressley lives in [[Dorchester, Boston|Dorchester, Massachusetts]] with her husband, Conan Harris,<ref name=BostonGlobe-ConanHarris-2017>{{cite news|last1=Irons|first1=Meghan E.|title=Her husband works for Walsh. Her political ally is challenging him. What's a city councilor to do?|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/02/06/her-husband-works-for-walsh-her-political-ally-challenging-him-what-city-councilor/l9qutFZeoWVIp1o9oDxh9N/story.html|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=February 6, 2017}}</ref> and her stepdaughter.<ref name=CityOfBoston-Profile-2018 /> Pressley rarely discusses her religious beliefs but has mentioned that she is a \"woman of faith\" who \"grew up in the church\".<ref>[https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2016/1/31/1477601/-Chris-Hayes-That-s-one-of-the-best-metaphors-I-ve-heard-in-this-campaign Chris Hayes: \"That's one of the best metaphors I've heard in this campaign...\"], Daily Kos, February 1, 2016</ref> Pressley does not drive an automobile and has never learned how to drive.<ref>{{cite news |last=Globe |first=Staff |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/01/31/things-about-ayanna-pressley/hJo1s12ZPJFJezn6GO7K3J/story.html |title=7 things about Ayanna Pressley |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=January 31, 2018 |accessdate=September 6, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nPressley has been public about being a child survivor of [[sexual abuse]].<ref name=WBUR-Turner-SexEd-2011>{{cite news|last1=Toness|first1=Bianca V\u00e1zquez|title=Pressley Is A Compelling, But Vulnerable Councilor|url=http://www.wbur.org/news/2011/02/15/pressley-profile|work=[[WBUR-FM]]|date=February 15, 2011|language=en}}</ref> She was also reportedly sexually assaulted while a student at Boston University.<ref name=TheGrio-100List-Profile-2012>{{cite news|title=TheGrio's 100: Ayanna Pressley, first black woman elected to Boston City Council overcomes life full of obstacles|url=https://thegrio.com/2012/01/30/2012-ayanna-pressley/|work=[[The Grio]]|date=January 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Pressley's husband, Conan Harris, resigned from his position as a senior public safety adviser at Boston City Hall to form his own [[consulting firm]], Conan Harris & Associates.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stout |first=Matt |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/02/16/ayanna-pressley-husband-left-city-hall-launch-consulting-firm-just-before-she-entered-congress/uDxhB2RiwOPuPNLU4x1MuK/story.html |title=Ayanna Pressley's husband left City Hall to launch consulting firm just before she entered Congress |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=February 16, 2019 |accessdate=July 10, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Pressley revealed that she had been diagnosed with [[alopecia areata]], resulting in the loss of all of her hair, and saying in a public announcement \"I want to be freed from the secret and the shame that that secret carries with it.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Moulite |first1=Jessica |title=Exclusive: Rep. Ayanna Pressley Reveals Beautiful Bald Head and Discusses Alopecia for the First Time |url=https://theglowup.theroot.com/exclusive-rep-ayanna-pressley-reveals-beautiful-bald-1841039847 |website=The Glow Up |accessdate=January 16, 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin no change | title=Democratic primary results}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = [[Ayanna Pressley]]\n  |votes      = 59,815\n  |percentage = 58.6\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = [[Mike Capuano]] (incumbent)\n  |votes      = 42,252\n  |percentage = 41.4\n  }}\n{{Election box total no change\n  | votes = 102,067\n  | percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change | title=Massachusetts' 7th congressional district, 2018}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link