tude d'une langue \u00e0 l'identit\u00e9 des langues |trans-title=Serbo-Croatian (Bosnian, Croatian, Montenegrin, Serbian): from the study of a language to the identity of languages |language=French |journal=Revue des \u00e9tudes slaves |volume=74 |issue=2\u20133 |pages=311\u2013325 |year=2003 |issn=0080-2557 |oclc=754204160 |id= {{ZDB|208723-6}} |ref= harv|doi=10.3406/slave.2002.6801 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* Banac, Ivo: ''Main Trends in the Croatian Language Question''. Yale University Press, 1984.\n* Bun\u010di\u0107, D., 2016. Serbo-Croatian/Serbian: Cyrillic and Latin. Biscriptality: A Sociolinguistic Typology, pp.&nbsp;231\u2013246.\n* Franoli\u0107, Branko: ''A Historical Survey of Literary Croatian''. Nouvelles \u00e9ditions Latines, Paris, 1984.\n* Franoli\u0107, B., 1983. The development of literary Croatian and Serbian. Buske Verlag.\n* {{cite book|last=Franoli\u0107 |first=Branko |authormask=2 |year=1988 |title=Language Policy in Yugoslavia with special reference to Croatian |publisher=Nouvelles Editions Latines |location=Paris}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Franoli\u0107 |first1=Branko |authormask=2 |last2=\u017dagar |first2=Mateo |year=2008 |title=A Historical Outline of Literary Croatian & The Glagolitic Heritage of Croatian Culture |publisher=Erasmus & CSYPN |location=London & Zagreb |isbn=978-953-6132-80-5}}\n* {{Cite journal|ref=harv|last=Greenberg|first=Robert D.|title=In the Aftermath of Yugoslavia's Collapse: The Politics of Language Death and Language Birth|journal=International Politics|year=1999|volume=36|issue=2|pages=141\u2013158}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Greenberg|first=Robert D.|chapter=Language, Religion, and Nationalism: The Case of the Former Serbo-Croatian|title=Typen slavischer Standardsprachen: Theoretische, methodische und empirische Zugaenge|year=2013|location=Wiesbaden|publisher=Harrassowitz Verlag|pages=217\u2013231|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XGUFngEACAAJ|isbn=9783447100281}}\n* Ivi\u0107, Pavle: ''Die serbokroatischen Dialekte''. the Hague, 1958.\n* {{cite book|last=Jakobsen |first=Per |editor1-last=Ostoji\u0107 |editor1-first=Branislav |title=Jezi\u010dka situacija u Crnoj Gori \u2013 norma i standardizacija |publisher=Crnogorska akademija nauka i umjetnosti |pages=25\u201334 |language=Serbo-Croatian |chapter=O strukturalno-lingvisti\u010dkim konstantama srpskohrvatskog jezika (inventar fonema i fonotakti\u010dka struktura) |trans-chapter=Serbocroatian structural-linguistic constants (inventory of phonemes and phonotactic structure) |location=Podgorica |year=2008 |isbn=978-86-7215-207-4}} <small>[http://vbcg.vbcg.me/scripts/cobiss?ukaz=DISP&id=0446469545391868&rec=8&sid=9 (COBISS-CG)]</small>.\n* {{cite journal|author=Kristophson, J\u00fcrgen |title=Vom Widersinn der Dialektologie: Gedanken zum \u0160tokavischen |trans-title=Dialectological Nonsense: Thoughts on Shtokavian |language=German |journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Balkanologie |volume=36 |issue=2 |pages=178\u2013186 |year=2000 |issn=0044-2356}} {{ZDB|201058-6}}.\n* Magner, Thomas F.: ''Zagreb Kajkavian dialect''. Pennsylvania State University, 1966.\n* {{cite book|last=Magner |first=Thomas F.|authormask=2 |year=1991 |title=Introduction to the Croatian and Serbian Language (Revised ed.) |publisher=Pennsylvania State University}}\n* {{cite book|last=Merk |first=Hening |editor1-last=Ostoji\u0107 |editor1-first=Branislav |title=Jezi\u010dka situacija u Crnoj Gori \u2013 norma i standardizacija |publisher=Crnogorska akademija nauka i umjetnosti |pages=295\u2013299 |language=Serbo-Croatian |chapter=Neka pragmati\u010dna zapa\u017eanja o postojanju srpskohrvatskog jezika |location=Podgorica |year=2008 |isbn=978-86-7215-207-4}} <small>[http://vbcg.vbcg.me/scripts/cobiss?ukaz=DISP&id=0446469545391868&rec=2&sid=8 (COBISS-CG)]</small>.\n* Murray Despalatovi\u0107, Elinor: ''Ljudevit Gaj and the Illyrian Movement''. Columbia University Press, 1975.\n* Spalatin, C., 1966. Serbo-Croatian or Serbian and Croatian?: Considerations on the Croatian Declaration and Serbian Proposal of March 1967. Journal of Croatian Studies, 7, pp.&nbsp;3\u201313.\n* Zekovic, Sreten & Cime\u0161a, Boro: ''Elementa montenegrina'', Chrestomatia 1/90. CIP, Zagreb 1991.\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{interWiki|code=sh}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Serbo-Croatian language}}\n* ''[[Ethnologue]]''{{spaced ndash}}the 15th edition of ''Ethnologue'' (released 2005) shows changes in this area:\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20131005004814/http://archive.ethnologue.com/14/show_language.asp?code=SRC Previous ''Ethnologue'' entry for Serbo-Croatian]\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20131005010950/http://archive.ethnologue.com/15/show_family.asp?subid=90675 ''Ethnologue'' 15th Edition report on western South Slavic languages]\n* [http://hjp.srce.hr/index.php?show=povijest&chapter=28-novosadski_dogovor Integral text of Novi Sad Agreement] {{in lang|hbs}}\n* [http://www.omniglot.com/writing/serbo-croat.htm Serbian and Croatian alphabets] at Omniglot.\n* [http://www.rferl.org/content/Serbian_Croatian_Bosnian_or_Montenegrin_Many_In_Balkans_Just_Call_It_Our_Language_/1497105.html \"Serbian, Croatian, Bosnian, Or Montenegrin? Or Just 'Our Language'?\"], [[Radio Free Europe]], February 21, 2009\n* {{Citation |last1=Browne |first1=Wayles |author1-link=Wayles Browne |last2=Alt |first2=Theresa |author2-link= |year=2004 |url=http://www.seelrc.org:8080/grammar/pdf/compgrammar_bcs.pdf |title=A Handbook of Bosnian, Serbian, and Croatian |publisher=SEELRC}}\n\n{{navboxes|\n|list =\n{{Languages of Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n{{Languages of Croatia}}\n{{Languages of Montenegro}}\n{{Languages of Serbia}}\n{{Slavic languages}}\n{{Dialects of Serbo-Croatian}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Serbo-Croatian Language}}\n[[Category:Serbo-Croatian language| ]]\n[[Category:Dialect levelling]]\n[[Category:Languages of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Languages of Croatia]]\n[[Category:Languages of Kosovo]]\n[[Category:Languages of Montenegro]]\n[[Category:Languages of Serbia]]\n[[Category:Languages of Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Languages of Vojvodina]]\n[[Category:South Slavic languages]]\n", "name_user": "DocWatson42", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected a misspelling.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serbo-Croatian"}
{"title_page": "U.D.O.", "text_new": "{{other uses|UDO (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist \n| name                = U.D.O.\n| image               = U.D.O. with Musikkorps der Bundeswehr \u2013 Wacken Open Air 2015 04.jpg\n| caption             = U.D.O. live in 2015\n| image_size          = 300\n| background          = group_or_band \n| origin              = [[Solingen]], Germany\n| genre               = [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]\n| years_active        = {{flatlist|\n* 1987\u20131992\n* 1996\u2013present}}\n| label               = [[AFM Records|AFM]], Breaker, [[GUN Records|GUN]], [[RCA Records|RCA]] \n| associated_acts     = [[Accept (band)|Accept]], [[Gotthard (band)|Gotthard]], [[Bullet (Swedish band)|Bullet]], Edge of Forever\n| website             = {{URL|http://www.udo-online.de/}}\n| current_members     = [[Udo Dirkschneider]]<br />Andrey Smirnov<br />Dee Dammers<br />Tilen Hudrap<br />Sven Dirkschneider\n| past_members        = Peter Szigeti<br />Frank Rittel<br />Mathias Dieth<br />Thomas Franke<br />Wolla B\u00f6hm<br />[[Dieter Rubach]]<br />[[Andy Susemihl]]<br />Thomas Smuszynski<br />[[Stefan Schwarzmann]]<br />Frank Fricke<br />Jurgen Graf<br />Lorenzo Milani<br />[[Stefan Kaufmann (musician)|Stefan Kaufmann]]<br />Igor Gianola<br />Francesco Jovino<br />[[Kasperi Heikkinen]]<br />[[Bill Hudson (guitarist)|Bill Hudson]]<br />Fitty Wienhold}}\n\n'''U.D.O.''' is a German [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band founded by lead vocalist [[Udo Dirkschneider]] in 1987. \n\n==History==\n===1987\u20131992===\nFollowing Udo Dirkschneider's departure from [[Accept (band)|Accept]] in 1987, he formed his own band called U.D.O. He recruited guitarists Mathias Dieth and Peter Szigeti, bassist Frank Rittel and drummer Thomas Franke. They released their debut album titled ''[[Animal House (U.D.O. album)|Animal House]]'' on 3 November 1987, which was entirely written by Accept. They would tour with the likes of [[Guns N' Roses]], [[Lita Ford]] and [[Zodiac Mindwarp]]. Rubach, Rittel and Franke departed the band, and guitarist Andy Susemihl, bassist Thomas Smuzyszki and drummer Stefan Schwarzmann joined. The follow-up album ''[[Mean Machine (U.D.O. album)|Mean Machine]]'' was released on 10 January 1989.\n\nSusemihl left the band, with U.D.O. now as a four-piece. The band shifted to a lighter approach with the third album ''[[Faceless World]]'', which was released on 25 February 1990, achieving great success; this being their best selling album so far. It was produced by former Accept drummer [[Stefan Kaufmann (musician)|Stefan Kaufmann]]. The fourth album ''[[Timebomb (album)|Timebomb]]'' was released on 3 April 1991. It was a more heavier album than their previous releases. In 1992, Dirkschneider put U.D.O. on hiatus to reunite with Accept.\n\n===1996\u2013present===\n[[File:U.D.O.-performing-live-at-Norway-Rock-Festival-2009.JPG|210px|thumb|left|U.D.O. performing live at [[Norway Rock Festival]] in 2009]]\nIn 1996, Dirkschneider reactivated U.D.O. with a brand new line-up; Stefan Kaufmann, now undertaking guitar duties, with guitarist J\u00fcrgen Graf and bassist Fitty Wienhold from Bullet, and Stefan Schwarzmann returning to the band. They took part in the 1997 compilation album ''[[A Tribute to Judas Priest: Legends of Metal]]'', in which they recorded the song \"Metal Gods\".\n\nOn 24 March 1997, U.D.O. released the fifth album ''[[Solid (U.D.O. album)|Solid]]''. It was featured on the [[Rock Hard (magazine)|Rock Hard]] magazine reader charts for more than a year after its release. The album was followed up with ''[[No Limits (U.D.O. album)|No Limits]]'' on 20 April 1998, featuring a similar songwriting approach from ''Solid''. The album features a cover of the Austrian pop band [[Supermax (band)|Supermax]]'s hit single \"Love Machine\". After the conclusion of the band's tour, Stefan Schwarzmann quit the band. New drummer Lorenzo Milani replaced him.\n\nThe seventh album ''[[Holy (U.D.O. album)|Holy]]'' was released on 18 October 1999, which received critical acclaim. It was a return to the guitar-driven sound similar to the ''[[Balls to the Wall]]''-era Accept. A world tour followed with dates in the United States and several other major countries. The band known as Vanize, fronted by Udo Dirkschneider's brother Peter, supported U.D.O. during the tour. Line-up changes occurred during the second part of the tour with [[Gotthard (band)|Gotthard]] guitarist Igor Gianola replacing J\u00fcrgen Graf. The tour spawned the first live album ''[[Live from Russia]]'', which was released on 15 October 2001, a 2-CD release featuring many of the classic Accept songs that have since become staples of U.D.O.'s set.\n\nOn 24 July 2002, the eighth album ''[[Man and Machine (U.D.O. album)|Man and Machine]]'' was released. It received a somewhat lukewarm reception. Despite standout songs such as the title track and \"Private Eye\", the album was ultimately less successful than ''Holy''. It is notable for the song \"Dancing with an Angel\", featuring a duet performance of Dirkschneider and vocalist [[Doro (musician)|Doro Pesch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-confirm-track-listing-for-man-and-machine/|title=U.D.O. Confirm Track Listing For \"Man And Machine\"!|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=21 December 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/dirkschneider-and-pesch-team-up-on-u-d-o-cd/|title=Dirkschneider And Pesch Team Up On U.D.O. CD|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=10 January 2002}}</ref>\n\nU.D.O. released their ninth studio album ''[[Thunderball (U.D.O. album)|Thunderball]]'' on 29 March 2004. The follow-up album ''[[Mission No. X]]'' was originally due for release on 4 October 2005, but was pushed forward by one week and was released on 30 September 2005 instead. It was the first album to feature Edge of Forever drummer Francesco Jovino.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-new-album-details-revealed-audio-samples-available/|title=U.D.O.: New Album Details Revealed, Audio Samples Available|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=7 June 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-mission-no-x-cover-artwork-posted-online/|title=U.D.O.: 'Mission No. X' Cover Artwork Posted Online|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=20 July 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-mission-no-x-to-arrive-one-week-earlier/|title=U.D.O.: 'Mission No. X' To Arrive One Week Earlier|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 September 2005}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 May 2007, the eleventh album ''[[Mastercutor]]'' was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-mastercutor-bonus-tracks-detailed-the-wrong-side-of-midnight-video-available/|title=U.D.O.: 'Mastercutor' Bonus Tracks Detailed; 'The Wrong Side Of Midnight' Video Available|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=9 May 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneider-discusses-new-u-d-o-album-mastercutor/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER Discusses New U.D.O. Album 'Mastercutor'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=16 June 2007}}</ref> In August 2007, bassist Fitty Weinhold was unable to perform with the band due to \"private reasons\". He would be temporarily replaced with former [[Majesty (band)|Majesty]] bassist Marcus Bielenberg for touring purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-recruits-temporary-bassist/|title=U.D.O. Recruits Temporary Bassist|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=4 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nU.D.O.'s twelfth studio album ''[[Dominator (U.D.O. album)|Dominator]]'' was released on 21 August 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-dominator-artwork-revealed/|title=U.D.O.: 'Dominator' Artwork Revealed|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=6 July 2009}}</ref> The next studio album ''[[Rev-Raptor]]'' was originally due for release on 14 January 2011, but was delayed until 18 March 2011 due to the recurrence of Stefan Kaufmann's back problems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-new-album-delayed/|title=U.D.O.: New Album Delayed|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=14 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-new-album-pushed-back-to-may/|title=U.D.O.: New Album Pushed Back To May|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=22 November 2010}}</ref> It received another delay, and was finally released on 20 May 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-complete-rev-raptor-album-details-revealed/|title=U.D.O.: Complete 'Rev-Raptor' Album Details Revealed|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=28 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, Kaufmann announced his departure for health reasons. He would continue to work in the surroundings of the band and produce for other bands in his own personal studio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bravewords.com/news/guitarist-stefan-kaufmann-leaves-u-d-o-band-seek-replacement|title=GUITARIST STEFAN KAUFMANN LEAVES U.D.O.; BAND SEEK REPLACEMENT|publisher=[[Bravewords.com]]|accessdate=12 September 2012}}</ref> On 15 January 2013, Russian guitarist Andrey Smirnov was recruited as the new member.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-announces-new-guitarist/|title=U.D.O. Announces New Guitarist|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=15 January 2013}}</ref> A week later, Igor Gianola left the band \"due to conflicts between band appointments and his private life and business.\" Following his departure, former [[Amberian Dawn]] guitarist [[Kasperi Heikkinen]] joined the band.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=88433|title=Guitarist Igor Gianola Leaves U.D.O., Replacement Announced|publisher=metalunderground.com|accessdate=24 January 2013}}</ref> The fourteenth album ''[[Steelhammer]]'' was released on 20 May 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-steelhammer-track-listing-revealed/|title=U.D.O.: 'Steelhammer' Track Listing Revealed|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=8 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, drummer Francesco Jovino left the band for personal reasons, joining [[Primal Fear (band)|Primal Fear]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bravewords.com/news/drummer-francesco-jovino-leaves-u-d-o-band-seek-replacement|title=DRUMMER FRANCESCO JOVINO LEAVES U.D.O.; BAND SEEK REPLACEMENT|publisher=[[Bravewords.com]]|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalstorm.net/events/news_comments.php?news_id=26753|title=Primal Fear - Drummer Aquiles Out, Francesco Jovino In|publisher=metalstorm.net|accessdate=14 June 2015}}</ref> He was replaced by Udo Dirkschneider's son Sven in February 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneiders-son-sven-joins-u-d-o-as-bands-drummer/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER's Son SVEN Joins U.D.O. As Band's Drummer|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> U.D.O. released the fifteenth studio album ''[[Decadent (U.D.O. album)|Decadent]]'' on 23 January 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-decadent-track-listing-revealed/|title=U.D.O.: 'Decadent' Track Listing Revealed|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Heikkinen announced his departure citing personal reasons. According to the band, no bad blood or drama were involved between the two.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/guitarist-kasperi-heikkinen-quits-u-d-o-and-dirkschneider/|title=Guitarist KASPERI HEIKKINEN Quits U.D.O. And DIRKSCHNEIDER|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=17 February 2017}}</ref> In March 2017, guitarist [[Bill Hudson (guitarist)|Bill Hudson]] was announced as the new member.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-and-dirkschneider-joined-by-guitarist-bill-hudson/|title=U.D.O. And DIRKSCHNEIDER Joined By Guitarist BILL HUDSON|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref> On 24 April 2018, Hudson parted ways with the band \"due to a difference in their individual visions for the future\", according to Dirkschneider, adding that there was no \"negative feelings on either side.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/guitarist-bill-hudson-exits-u-d-o-and-dirkschneider-after-only-a-year/|title=Guitarist BILL HUDSON Exits U.D.O. And DIRKSCHNEIDER After Only A Year|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/guitarist-bill-hudson-sets-record-straight-regarding-his-exit-from-dirkschneider/|title=Guitarist BILL HUDSON Sets Record Straight Regarding His Exit From DIRKSCHNEIDER|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneider-comments-on-recent-u-d-o-lineup-changes-i-want-to-have-fresh-blood-in-the-band/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER Comments On Recent U.D.O. Lineup Changes: 'I Want To Have Fresh Blood In The Band'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=25 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalforcesmagazine.com/site/feature-udo-08-18/|title=U.D.O. \u2013 The Tank Drives On|publisher=[[Metal Forces]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/ex-u-d-o-guitarist-kasperi-heikkinen-fires-back-at-udo-dirkschneider-his-comments-are-bitter-and-unprofessional/|title=Ex-U.D.O. Guitarist KASPERI HEIKKINEN Fires Back At UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER: His Comments Are 'Bitter' And 'Unprofessional'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> In June 2018, Stefan Kaufmann temporarily rejoined the band only for the summer festival appearances until a new guitarist was found.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-rejoined-by-guitarist-stefan-kaufmann-for-summer-festival-appearances/|title=U.D.O. Rejoined By Guitarist STEFAN KAUFMANN For Summer Festival Appearances|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref> The sixteenth album ''[[Steelfactory]]'' was released on 31 August 2018, with the first single \"Rising High\" being made available for streaming.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-to-release-steelfactory-album-in-august-first-single-rising-high-now-available/|title=U.D.O. To Release 'Steelfactory' Album In August; First Single 'Rising High' Now Available|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref> On 19 September 2018, bassist Fitty Wienhold announced his departure from U.D.O., but stated that he would remain with the band if needed, \"as a songwriter, as a friend, as an advisor...whatever.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/bassist-fitty-wienhold-exits-u-d-o-after-22-years/|title=Bassist FITTY WIENHOLD Exits U.D.O. After 22 Years|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref> The band soon recruited guitarist Dee Dammers and world renowned bassist Tilen Hudrap (Pestilence, Paradox, Vicious Rumors,...) as their new members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-announces-new-guitarist-and-bassist/|title=U.D.O. Announces New Guitarist And Bassist|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=6 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring U.D.O.'s touring in Europe in early 2019, Dirkschneider performed as a handicap after experiencing left knee pain. He vowed to continue without doctors' advice and without causing disappointment to the fans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneider-ignores-doctors-advice-will-tour-with-u-d-o-despite-serious-health-issue/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER Ignores Doctors' Advice, Will Tour With U.D.O. Despite 'Serious Health' Issue|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=19 January 2019}}</ref> In September 2019, the band announced that they would perform Accept's 1985 album ''[[Metal Heart]]'' in its entirety at the [[Wacken Open Air]] festival in 2020 to celebrate its 35th anniversary, with the addition of the music corps of the [[Bundeswehr|German Armed Forces]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneider-to-perform-accepts-metal-heart-album-in-its-entirety-at-next-years-wacken-open-air/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER To Perform ACCEPT's 'Metal Heart' Album In Its Entirety At Next Year's WACKEN OPEN AIR|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Side Project==\nU.D.O. performed under the name Dirkschneider for an occasion in which Udo Dirkschneider described as his \"farewell to Accept\", stating that he would no longer perform Accept songs again in the band's live shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneider-to-embark-on-special-accept-farewell-tour-in-2016/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER To Embark On Special ACCEPT 'Farewell' Tour In 2016|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=1 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneider-explains-decision-to-close-the-accept-chapter/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER Explains Decision To 'Close The ACCEPT Chapter'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref> In early 2017, they performed in North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneider-announces-north-american-back-to-the-roots-farewell-to-accept-tour/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER Announces North American 'Back To The Roots - Farewell To ACCEPT' Tour|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref> A 2-CD live album titled ''Live - Back to the Roots'' was released on 28 October 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/dirkschneider-to-release-live-back-to-the-roots-album-in-october/|title=DIRKSCHNEIDER To Release 'Live - Back To The Roots' Album In October|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref> An updated version titled ''Live - Back to the Roots - Accepted!'' was released on 4 August 2017, featuring a DVD of their performance from [[Brno]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/dirkschneider-to-release-live-back-to-the-roots-accepted-in-august/|title=DIRKSCHNEIDER To Release 'Live - Back To The Roots - Accepted!' In August|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nDirkschneider continued to perform Accept songs for at least another year, due to the request from fans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneider-to-continue-performing-accept-classics-for-at-least-another-year/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER To Continue Performing ACCEPT Classics For At Least Another Year|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=21 March 2017}}</ref> The band returned to North America for a second time in early 2018 after a positive reception from their first visit the previous year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/dirkschneider-to-return-to-north-america-in-early-2018/|title=DIRKSCHNEIDER To Return To North America In Early 2018|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref> In 2018, Udo Dirkschneider put his side project to a close as he did not want to cause confusion between his main band and his side project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/former-accept-frontman-udo-dirkschneider-doesnt-want-to-confuse-people-by-continuing-namesake-dirkschneider-band/|title=Former ACCEPT Frontman UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER Doesn't Want To Confuse People By Continuing Namesake 'DIRKSCHNEIDER' Band|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|U.D.O. discography}}\n* ''[[Animal House (U.D.O. album)|Animal House]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Mean Machine (U.D.O. album)|Mean Machine]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Faceless World]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Timebomb (album)|Timebomb]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Solid (U.D.O. album)|Solid]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[No Limits (U.D.O. album)|No Limits]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Holy (U.D.O. album)|Holy]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Man and Machine (U.D.O. album)|Man and Machine]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Thunderball (U.D.O. album)|Thunderball]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Mission No. X]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Mastercutor]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Dominator (U.D.O. album)|Dominator]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Rev-Raptor]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Steelhammer]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Decadent (U.D.O. album)|Decadent]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Steelfactory]]'' (2018)\n\n==Band members==\n{{main|List of U.D.O. band members}}\n'''Current members'''\n* [[Udo Dirkschneider]] \u2013 vocals {{small|(1987\u20131992,1996\u2013present)}}\n* Andrey Smirnov \u2013 guitars {{small|(2013\u2013present)}}\n* Sven Dirkschneider \u2013 drums {{small|(2015\u2013present)}}\n* Tilen Hudrap \u2013 bass {{small|(2018\u2013present)}}\n* Dee Dammers \u2013 guitars {{small|(2018\u2013present)}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Darxon]]\n* [[Kreator]]\n* [[Sinner (band)|Sinner]]\n* [[Gravestone (band)|Gravestone]]\n* [[Saxon (band)|Saxon]]\n* [[Teutonic thrash metal]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|1=http://www.udo-online.de/}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110513010555/http://www.metalpaths.com/interviews/u-d-o-udo-dirkschneider,6712 Interview with Udo Dirkschneider @ Metalpaths.com (2011)]\n\n{{U.D.O.}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Udo}}\n[[Category:1987 establishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:German heavy metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1987]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|UDO (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist \n| name                = U.D.O.\n| image               = U.D.O. with Musikkorps der Bundeswehr \u2013 Wacken Open Air 2015 04.jpg\n| caption             = U.D.O. live in 2015\n| image_size          = 300\n| background          = group_or_band \n| origin              = [[Solingen]], Germany\n| genre               = [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]\n| years_active        = {{flatlist|\n* 1987\u20131992\n* 1996\u2013present}}\n| label               = [[AFM Records|AFM]], Breaker, [[GUN Records|GUN]], [[RCA Records|RCA]] \n| associated_acts     = [[Accept (band)|Accept]], [[Gotthard (band)|Gotthard]], [[Bullet (Swedish band)|Bullet]], Edge of Forever\n| website             = {{URL|http://www.udo-online.de/}}\n| current_members     = [[Udo Dirkschneider]]<br />Andrey Smirnov<br />Dee Dammers<br />Tilen Hudrap<br />Sven Dirkschneider\n| past_members        = Peter Szigeti<br />Frank Rittel<br />Mathias Dieth<br />Thomas Franke<br />Wolla B\u00f6hm<br />[[Dieter Rubach]]<br />[[Andy Susemihl]]<br />Thomas Smuszynski<br />[[Stefan Schwarzmann]]<br />Frank Fricke<br />Jurgen Graf<br />Lorenzo Milani<br />[[Stefan Kaufmann (musician)|Stefan Kaufmann]]<br />Igor Gianola<br />Francesco Jovino<br />[[Kasperi Heikkinen]]<br />[[Bill Hudson (guitarist)|Bill Hudson]]<br />Fitty Wienhold}}\n\n'''U.D.O.''' is a German [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band founded by lead vocalist [[Udo Dirkschneider]] in 1987.\n\n==History==\n===1987\u20131992===\nFollowing Udo Dirkschneider's departure from [[Accept (band)|Accept]] in 1987, he formed his own band called U.D.O. He recruited guitarists Mathias Dieth and Peter Szigeti, bassist Frank Rittel and drummer Thomas Franke. They released their debut album titled ''[[Animal House (U.D.O. album)|Animal House]]'' on 3 November 1987, which was entirely written by Accept. They would tour with the likes of [[Guns N' Roses]], [[Lita Ford]] and [[Zodiac Mindwarp]]. Rubach, Rittel and Franke departed the band, and guitarist Andy Susemihl, bassist Thomas Smuzyszki and drummer Stefan Schwarzmann joined. The follow-up album ''[[Mean Machine (U.D.O. album)|Mean Machine]]'' was released on 10 January 1989.\n\nSusemihl left the band, with U.D.O. now as a four-piece. The band shifted to a lighter approach with the third album ''[[Faceless World]]'', which was released on 25 February 1990, achieving great success; this being their best selling album so far. It was produced by former Accept drummer [[Stefan Kaufmann (musician)|Stefan Kaufmann]]. The fourth album ''[[Timebomb (album)|Timebomb]]'' was released on 3 April 1991. It was a more heavier album than their previous releases. In 1992, Dirkschneider put U.D.O. on hiatus to reunite with Accept.\n\n===1996\u2013present===\n[[File:U.D.O.-performing-live-at-Norway-Rock-Festival-2009.JPG|210px|thumb|left|U.D.O. performing live at [[Norway Rock Festival]] in 2009]]\nIn 1996, Dirkschneider reactivated U.D.O. with a brand new line-up; Stefan Kaufmann, now undertaking guitar duties, with guitarist J\u00fcrgen Graf and bassist Fitty Wienhold from Bullet, and Stefan Schwarzmann returning to the band. They took part in the 1997 compilation album ''[[A Tribute to Judas Priest: Legends of Metal]]'', in which they recorded the song \"Metal Gods\".\n\nOn 24 March 1997, U.D.O. released the fifth album ''[[Solid (U.D.O. album)|Solid]]''. It was featured on the [[Rock Hard (magazine)|Rock Hard]] magazine reader charts for more than a year after its release. The album was followed up with ''[[No Limits (U.D.O. album)|No Limits]]'' on 20 April 1998, featuring a similar songwriting approach from ''Solid''. The album features a cover of the Austrian pop band [[Supermax (band)|Supermax]]'s hit single \"Love Machine\". After the conclusion of the band's tour, Stefan Schwarzmann quit the band. New drummer Lorenzo Milani replaced him.\n\nThe seventh album ''[[Holy (U.D.O. album)|Holy]]'' was released on 18 October 1999, which received critical acclaim. It was a return to the guitar-driven sound similar to the ''[[Balls to the Wall]]''-era Accept. A world tour followed with dates in the United States and several other major countries. The band known as Vanize, fronted by Udo Dirkschneider's brother Peter, supported U.D.O. during the tour. Line-up changes occurred during the second part of the tour with [[Gotthard (band)|Gotthard]] guitarist Igor Gianola replacing J\u00fcrgen Graf. The tour spawned the first live album ''[[Live from Russia]]'', which was released on 15 October 2001, a 2-CD release featuring many of the classic Accept songs that have since become staples of U.D.O.'s set.\n\nOn 24 July 2002, the eighth album ''[[Man and Machine (U.D.O. album)|Man and Machine]]'' was released. It received a somewhat lukewarm reception. Despite standout songs such as the title track and \"Private Eye\", the album was ultimately less successful than ''Holy''. It is notable for the song \"Dancing with an Angel\", featuring a duet performance of Dirkschneider and vocalist [[Doro (musician)|Doro Pesch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-confirm-track-listing-for-man-and-machine/|title=U.D.O. Confirm Track Listing For \"Man And Machine\"!|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=21 December 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/dirkschneider-and-pesch-team-up-on-u-d-o-cd/|title=Dirkschneider And Pesch Team Up On U.D.O. CD|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=10 January 2002}}</ref>\n\nU.D.O. released their ninth studio album ''[[Thunderball (U.D.O. album)|Thunderball]]'' on 29 March 2004. The follow-up album ''[[Mission No. X]]'' was originally due for release on 4 October 2005, but was pushed forward by one week and was released on 30 September 2005 instead. It was the first album to feature Edge of Forever drummer Francesco Jovino.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-new-album-details-revealed-audio-samples-available/|title=U.D.O.: New Album Details Revealed, Audio Samples Available|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=7 June 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-mission-no-x-cover-artwork-posted-online/|title=U.D.O.: 'Mission No. X' Cover Artwork Posted Online|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=20 July 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-mission-no-x-to-arrive-one-week-earlier/|title=U.D.O.: 'Mission No. X' To Arrive One Week Earlier|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 September 2005}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 May 2007, the eleventh album ''[[Mastercutor]]'' was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-mastercutor-bonus-tracks-detailed-the-wrong-side-of-midnight-video-available/|title=U.D.O.: 'Mastercutor' Bonus Tracks Detailed; 'The Wrong Side Of Midnight' Video Available|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=9 May 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneider-discusses-new-u-d-o-album-mastercutor/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER Discusses New U.D.O. Album 'Mastercutor'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=16 June 2007}}</ref> In August 2007, bassist Fitty Weinhold was unable to perform with the band due to \"private reasons\". He would be temporarily replaced with former [[Majesty (band)|Majesty]] bassist Marcus Bielenberg for touring purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-recruits-temporary-bassist/|title=U.D.O. Recruits Temporary Bassist|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=4 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nU.D.O.'s twelfth studio album ''[[Dominator (U.D.O. album)|Dominator]]'' was released on 21 August 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-dominator-artwork-revealed/|title=U.D.O.: 'Dominator' Artwork Revealed|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=6 July 2009}}</ref> The next studio album ''[[Rev-Raptor]]'' was originally due for release on 14 January 2011, but was delayed until 18 March 2011 due to the recurrence of Stefan Kaufmann's back problems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-new-album-delayed/|title=U.D.O.: New Album Delayed|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=14 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-new-album-pushed-back-to-may/|title=U.D.O.: New Album Pushed Back To May|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=22 November 2010}}</ref> It received another delay, and was finally released on 20 May 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-complete-rev-raptor-album-details-revealed/|title=U.D.O.: Complete 'Rev-Raptor' Album Details Revealed|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=28 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, Kaufmann announced his departure for health reasons. He would continue to work in the surroundings of the band and produce for other bands in his own personal studio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bravewords.com/news/guitarist-stefan-kaufmann-leaves-u-d-o-band-seek-replacement|title=GUITARIST STEFAN KAUFMANN LEAVES U.D.O.; BAND SEEK REPLACEMENT|publisher=[[Bravewords.com]]|accessdate=12 September 2012}}</ref> On 15 January 2013, Russian guitarist Andrey Smirnov was recruited as the new member.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-announces-new-guitarist/|title=U.D.O. Announces New Guitarist|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=15 January 2013}}</ref> A week later, Igor Gianola left the band \"due to conflicts between band appointments and his private life and business.\" Following his departure, former [[Amberian Dawn]] guitarist [[Kasperi Heikkinen]] joined the band.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=88433|title=Guitarist Igor Gianola Leaves U.D.O., Replacement Announced|publisher=metalunderground.com|accessdate=24 January 2013}}</ref> The fourteenth album ''[[Steelhammer]]'' was released on 20 May 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-steelhammer-track-listing-revealed/|title=U.D.O.: 'Steelhammer' Track Listing Revealed|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=8 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, drummer Francesco Jovino left the band for personal reasons, joining [[Primal Fear (band)|Primal Fear]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bravewords.com/news/drummer-francesco-jovino-leaves-u-d-o-band-seek-replacement|title=DRUMMER FRANCESCO JOVINO LEAVES U.D.O.; BAND SEEK REPLACEMENT|publisher=[[Bravewords.com]]|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalstorm.net/events/news_comments.php?news_id=26753|title=Primal Fear - Drummer Aquiles Out, Francesco Jovino In|publisher=metalstorm.net|accessdate=14 June 2015}}</ref> He was replaced by Udo Dirkschneider's son Sven in February 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneiders-son-sven-joins-u-d-o-as-bands-drummer/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER's Son SVEN Joins U.D.O. As Band's Drummer|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> U.D.O. released the fifteenth studio album ''[[Decadent (U.D.O. album)|Decadent]]'' on 23 January 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-decadent-track-listing-revealed/|title=U.D.O.: 'Decadent' Track Listing Revealed|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Heikkinen announced his departure citing personal reasons. According to the band, no bad blood or drama were involved between the two.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/guitarist-kasperi-heikkinen-quits-u-d-o-and-dirkschneider/|title=Guitarist KASPERI HEIKKINEN Quits U.D.O. And DIRKSCHNEIDER|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=17 February 2017}}</ref> In March 2017, guitarist [[Bill Hudson (guitarist)|Bill Hudson]] was announced as the new member.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-and-dirkschneider-joined-by-guitarist-bill-hudson/|title=U.D.O. And DIRKSCHNEIDER Joined By Guitarist BILL HUDSON|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref> On 24 April 2018, Hudson parted ways with the band \"due to a difference in their individual visions for the future\", according to Dirkschneider, adding that there was no \"negative feelings on either side.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/guitarist-bill-hudson-exits-u-d-o-and-dirkschneider-after-only-a-year/|title=Guitarist BILL HUDSON Exits U.D.O. And DIRKSCHNEIDER After Only A Year|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/guitarist-bill-hudson-sets-record-straight-regarding-his-exit-from-dirkschneider/|title=Guitarist BILL HUDSON Sets Record Straight Regarding His Exit From DIRKSCHNEIDER|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneider-comments-on-recent-u-d-o-lineup-changes-i-want-to-have-fresh-blood-in-the-band/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER Comments On Recent U.D.O. Lineup Changes: 'I Want To Have Fresh Blood In The Band'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=25 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalforcesmagazine.com/site/feature-udo-08-18/|title=U.D.O. \u2013 The Tank Drives On|publisher=[[Metal Forces]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/ex-u-d-o-guitarist-kasperi-heikkinen-fires-back-at-udo-dirkschneider-his-comments-are-bitter-and-unprofessional/|title=Ex-U.D.O. Guitarist KASPERI HEIKKINEN Fires Back At UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER: His Comments Are 'Bitter' And 'Unprofessional'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> In June 2018, Stefan Kaufmann temporarily rejoined the band only for the summer festival appearances until a new guitarist was found.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-rejoined-by-guitarist-stefan-kaufmann-for-summer-festival-appearances/|title=U.D.O. Rejoined By Guitarist STEFAN KAUFMANN For Summer Festival Appearances|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref> The sixteenth album ''[[Steelfactory]]'' was released on 31 August 2018, with the first single \"Rising High\" being made available for streaming.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-to-release-steelfactory-album-in-august-first-single-rising-high-now-available/|title=U.D.O. To Release 'Steelfactory' Album In August; First Single 'Rising High' Now Available|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref> On 19 September 2018, bassist Fitty Wienhold announced his departure from U.D.O., but stated that he would remain with the band if needed, \"as a songwriter, as a friend, as an advisor...whatever.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/bassist-fitty-wienhold-exits-u-d-o-after-22-years/|title=Bassist FITTY WIENHOLD Exits U.D.O. After 22 Years|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref> The band soon recruited guitarist Dee Dammers and world renowned bassist Tilen Hudrap (Pestilence, Paradox, Vicious Rumors,...) as their new members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/u-d-o-announces-new-guitarist-and-bassist/|title=U.D.O. Announces New Guitarist And Bassist|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=6 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring U.D.O.'s touring in Europe in early 2019, Dirkschneider performed as a handicap after experiencing left knee pain. He vowed to continue without doctors' advice and without causing disappointment to the fans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneider-ignores-doctors-advice-will-tour-with-u-d-o-despite-serious-health-issue/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER Ignores Doctors' Advice, Will Tour With U.D.O. Despite 'Serious Health' Issue|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=19 January 2019}}</ref> In September 2019, the band announced that they would perform Accept's 1985 album ''[[Metal Heart]]'' in its entirety at the [[Wacken Open Air]] festival in 2020 to celebrate its 35th anniversary, with the addition of the music corps of the [[Bundeswehr|German Armed Forces]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneider-to-perform-accepts-metal-heart-album-in-its-entirety-at-next-years-wacken-open-air/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER To Perform ACCEPT's 'Metal Heart' Album In Its Entirety At Next Year's WACKEN OPEN AIR|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Side Project==\nU.D.O. performed under the name Dirkschneider for an occasion in which Udo Dirkschneider described as his \"farewell to Accept\", stating that he would no longer perform Accept songs again in the band's live shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneider-to-embark-on-special-accept-farewell-tour-in-2016/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER To Embark On Special ACCEPT 'Farewell' Tour In 2016|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=1 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneider-explains-decision-to-close-the-accept-chapter/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER Explains Decision To 'Close The ACCEPT Chapter'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref> In early 2017, they performed in North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneider-announces-north-american-back-to-the-roots-farewell-to-accept-tour/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER Announces North American 'Back To The Roots - Farewell To ACCEPT' Tour|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref> A 2-CD live album titled ''Live - Back to the Roots'' was released on 28 October 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/dirkschneider-to-release-live-back-to-the-roots-album-in-october/|title=DIRKSCHNEIDER To Release 'Live - Back To The Roots' Album In October|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref> An updated version titled ''Live - Back to the Roots - Accepted!'' was released on 4 August 2017, featuring a DVD of their performance from [[Brno]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/dirkschneider-to-release-live-back-to-the-roots-accepted-in-august/|title=DIRKSCHNEIDER To Release 'Live - Back To The Roots - Accepted!' In August|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nDirkschneider continued to perform Accept songs for at least another year, due to the request from fans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/udo-dirkschneider-to-continue-performing-accept-classics-for-at-least-another-year/|title=UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER To Continue Performing ACCEPT Classics For At Least Another Year|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=21 March 2017}}</ref> The band returned to North America for a second time in early 2018 after a positive reception from their first visit the previous year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/dirkschneider-to-return-to-north-america-in-early-2018/|title=DIRKSCHNEIDER To Return To North America In Early 2018|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref> In 2018, Udo Dirkschneider put his side project to a close as he did not want to cause confusion between his main band and his side project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/former-accept-frontman-udo-dirkschneider-doesnt-want-to-confuse-people-by-continuing-namesake-dirkschneider-band/|title=Former ACCEPT Frontman UDO DIRKSCHNEIDER Doesn't Want To Confuse People By Continuing Namesake 'DIRKSCHNEIDER' Band|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|U.D.O. discography}}\n* ''[[Animal House (U.D.O. album)|Animal House]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Mean Machine (U.D.O. album)|Mean Machine]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Faceless World]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Timebomb (album)|Timebomb]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Solid (U.D.O. album)|Solid]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[No Limits (U.D.O. album)|No Limits]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Holy (U.D.O. album)|Holy]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Man and Machine (U.D.O. album)|Man and Machine]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Thunderball (U.D.O. album)|Thunderball]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Mission No. X]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Mastercutor]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Dominator (U.D.O. album)|Dominator]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Rev-Raptor]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Steelhammer]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Decadent (U.D.O. album)|Decadent]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Steelfactory]]'' (2018)\n\n==Band members==\n{{main|List of U.D.O. band members}}\n'''Current members'''\n* [[Udo Dirkschneider]] \u2013 vocals {{small|(1987\u20131992,1996\u2013present)}}\n* Andrey Smirnov \u2013 guitars {{small|(2013\u2013present)}}\n* Sven Dirkschneider \u2013 drums {{small|(2015\u2013present)}}\n* Tilen Hudrap \u2013 bass {{small|(2018\u2013present)}}\n* Dee Dammers \u2013 guitars {{small|(2018\u2013present)}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Darxon]]\n* [[Kreator]]\n* [[Sinner (band)|Sinner]]\n* [[Gravestone (band)|Gravestone]]\n* [[Saxon (band)|Saxon]]\n* [[Teutonic thrash metal]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|1=http://www.udo-online.de/}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110513010555/http://www.metalpaths.com/interviews/u-d-o-udo-dirkschneider,6712 Interview with Udo Dirkschneider @ Metalpaths.com (2011)]\n\n{{U.D.O.}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Udo}}\n[[Category:1987 establishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:German heavy metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1987]]\n", "name_user": "122.179.204.149", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U.D.O."}
{"title_page": "Project Hotfoot (Laos)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|text=the later rescue mission into Iran to save EDS employees, [[Operation HOTFOOT]]}}\n{{Infobox military operation\n |name          = Project Hotfoot\n |partof        = [[Laotian Civil War]], [[Vietnam War]], and the [[Cold War (1953\u20131962)#Indochina|Cold War in Indochina]]\n |type          = Military training mission\n |location      = [[Kingdom of Laos]]\n |planned_by    = John Heintges, [[United States Indo-Pacific Command#History|CINCPAC]]\n |commanded_by  = [[Donald Blackburn]], [[Arthur D. Simons]], Andrew Jackson Boyle\n |objective     = Train soldiers in the [[Royal Lao Army]], cooperate with French military training teams\n |date          = {{start date|1959|01|22|df=y}}\u2014{{End date|1961|19|04}}\n |executed_by   = [[United States Army Special Forces]] Mobile Training Teams, US control team, French training teams\n |outcome       = Multiple units trained; project develops into [[Operation White Star]]; [[Kong Le]] prepares to lead a [[1960 Laotian coups#Kong Le's coup|military coup against the Kingdom of Laos]]\n |fatalities    = 5\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Laotian Civil War}}\n\n'''Project Hotfoot''' (also known as Operation Hotfoot, originally known as Operation Ambidextrous<ref>Annie Jacobsen, \"Surprise, Kill, Vanish: The Secret History of CIA Paramilitary Armies, Operators, and Assassins,\" (New York: Little, Brown and Company, 2019), p. 112</ref> ) was a secretive military training mission from the United States in support of the [[Kingdom of Laos]]. It ran from 22 January 1959 through 19 April 1961. Working in civilian clothing in conjunction with a French military mission, it concentrated on technical training of the [[Royal Lao Army]].\n\n==Background==\n\nIn March 1945, in the waning days of World War II, the Japanese occupiers of the [[Kingdom of Laos]] forced Lao independence from France. However, the French reasserted themselves in [[French Indochina]] after war's end. During the ensuing [[First Indochina War]], the [[Vietminh|Vietnamese Communist revolutionists]] invaded Laos in March 1953. After occupying large portions of [[Phongsaly]], [[Houaphanh Province]], and mountainous terrain that would become the [[Ho Chi Minh Trail]], the Vietminh moved south to the [[Plain of Jars]] and in a column menacing [[Luang Prabang]]. The Plain of Jars offered the French forces the advantages of attacking the Viet Minh in the open with artillery and air strikes; that assault was halted. The column near Luang Prabang was also stopped when it was ambushed. A third Vietminh force captured [[Thakhek]] on 25 December 1953, cutting Laos in two. This force would not be evicted until February 1954.<ref>Anthony, Sexton, p. 8.</ref>\n\nAs France departed Laos after losing the First Indochina War, the United States moved in to support the [[Royal Lao Government]]. In the wake of the [[1954 Geneva Conference]] and its treaties, the U.S. embassy in [[Vientiane]] established the [[Programs Evaluation Office]] to oversee military aid to Laos. It was established on 13 December 1954. Purportedly staffed by civilians, its personnel were U.S. military retirees, veterans, and reservists. Because the PEO personnel were not serving on active military duty, they were not in violation of the terms of the Geneva treaty.<ref>Castle, pp. 7\u201317.</ref>\n\n==The Heintges Plan==\n\nIn September 1958, Brigadier General [[John A. Heintges]] left the U.S. Army. In November, he flew to Laos to evaluate the Programs Evaluation Office, with a mandate to take charge of it. Heintges concluded that the staff of the PEO was too small, and seemed intent only on delivering equipment. There was a suspicion that some military aid to Laos was diverted for French use in the [[Algerian War]].<ref name=conboy20>Conboy, Morrison, p. 20.</ref>\n\nReturning to Washington, DC, Heintges lobbied for a larger PEO. He pointed to the sad shape of the [[Royal Lao Army]] as proof of need of U.S. military materiel and training. He was granted an increase in staff. Also, on 22 January 1959, [[CINCPAC]] levied a requirement for 12 [[Special Forces (United States Army)|Special Forces]] Mobile Training Teams of eight men each; they were slated to start six months temporary duty in Laos on 1 April.<ref name=conboy20/>  The operation was kept secret from the American public and, in fact, U.S. commandos that were sent to Laos were given written orders stating they were going to Vietnam.<ref>Annie Jacobsen, \"Surprise, Kill, Vanish: The Secret History of CIA Paramilitary Armies, Operators, and Assassins,\" (New York: Little, Brown and Company, 2019), p. 112</ref> A cover story was arranged; the U.S. mission was purportedly from the [[U.S. National Geodetic Survey]].<ref name=guardia155/> U.S. commandos were disguised as [[civilian]]s and carried civilian identifications.<ref>Annie Jacobsen, \"Surprise, Kill, Vanish: The Secret History of CIA Paramilitary Armies, Operators, and Assassins,\" (New York: Little, Brown and Company, 2019), p. 113</ref> General [[Donald Blackburn]] was charged with command of the mission. He prepared his men by requiring tutoring in both French and Lao, and insisting that all hands read the nonfiction book ''[[Street Without Joy]]'', as well as the novel ''[[The Ugly American]]'', before departure.<ref name=guardia155>Guardia, pp. 155\u2013156.</ref><ref>Gillespie, p. 50.</ref>\n\nHowever, negotiations with the French government delayed things. It was finally decided that the French instructors in Laos under the Geneva treaty would continue to teach tactics, while the American trainers would teach technical subjects. On 24 July 1959, the Mobile Training Teams arrived in [[Vientiane]]. Augmented by a control team 11 strong, the force was dubbed Project Hotfoot (Operation Hotfoot for security purposes); it was also known by the official but little-used title of the Laos Training Advisory Group. They were to work for the PEO as a training arm, teaching Lao soldiers the use of the [[M1 Garand]], [[Browning Automatic Rifle]], [[M1 Carbine]], [[bazooka]], [[M18 recoilless rifle]], and both 60mm and 81mm [[Mortar (weapon)|mortars]]. The Green Berets were commanded on site by Lieutenant Colonel [[Arthur D. Simons]].<ref>Conboy, Morrison, pp. 20\u201321.</ref>\n\n==Hotfoot at work==\n\nHaving been delayed in arrival, the Hotfoot contingent now found itself balked by Lao internal politics. While waiting for the local political situation to clear, the Hotfoot specialists hunkered in training centers at [[Luang Prabang]], [[Savannakhet]], [[Pakse]], and Vientiane. They surveyed the Royal Lao Army as they waited. By the time they were free to begin training at the beginning of September 1959, they had an excellent idea of the retraining task before them. Nine of the Mobile Training Teams were matched with French training teams at regional training camps. Three teams were assigned to build a new training facility northeast of Vientiane on Route 13 at Kilometer 22. This center would be an all-Hotfoot operation, with no French involved. Nearby, at Kilometer 17, they built a ranger training center.<ref>Conboy, Morrison, pp. 23\u201324.</ref>\n\nOn 25 November 1959, one of the Green Beret teams moved from Savannakhet into Military Region 2. They co-located at Khang Khay with a French training team and began building a clinic, rifle range, and demolitions practice area. As 1960 began, training of both regular and [[irregular military]] troops began. The latter were [[Auto Defense Choc]] guerrillas.<ref>Conboy, Morrison, p. 24.</ref>\n\nThe original Hotfoot contingent rotated out of Laos in February 1960, to be replaced by Hotfoot II. The new crew began ranger training for the RLA's ''1 Bataillon Parachutistes'' (1st Paratroop Battalion) and ''2 Bataillon Parachutistes'' (2d Paratroop Battalion). As Hotfoot II left Laos on 29 June 1960, to be replaced by Hotfoot III, 2nd BP began erecting a new battalion encampment for itself at KM 22. On 9 August, the 2nd BP commander, [[Kong Le]], would stage [[1960 Laotian coups#Kong Le's coup|his coup]] from there, commanding his loyal paratroopers.<ref>Conboy, Morrison, pp. 31\u201332.</ref>\n\n==Hotfoot becomes White Star==\n\nUnder incoming American President [[John F. Kennedy]], Hotfoot was rapidly expanded. Andrew Jackson Boyle had just been appointed as chief of the PEO; on 31 January 1961, just after the 19 January [[inauguration]], he requested nine more training teams. His rationale was that every existing or forming battalion in the Royal Lao Army should have an American advisor. The Pentagon signed off on the request, with three packets each consisting of three teams staggering their arrivals in Laos from March through May 1961. The Operation Hotfoot moniker changed to Operation Monkhood.<ref>Conboy, Morrison, p. 50.</ref>\n\nOn 19 April 1961, President Kennedy made a symbolic gesture in allowing the PEO to publicly become a MAAG; PEO members were allowed to don uniforms and resume usual public military courtesies. At the same time, the Hotfoot V teams were also renamed as [[Operation White Star]]. Operation Hotfoot had suffered five killed in action during its duties.<ref>Conboy, Morrison, p. 53.</ref><ref>Hall, pp. 331\u2013332.</ref> When Lieutenant Colonel Simons later organized the [[Operation Ivory Coast|Raid on Son Tay]], he would call upon men who served with him in Laos, such as [[Richard Meadows]] and [[Elliott P. Sydnor, Jr.]].<ref>Hall, pp. 411\u2013413.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n\n* Anthony, Victor B. and Richard R. Sexton (1993). ''The War in Northern Laos''. Command for Air Force History. OCLC 232549943.\n* Castle, Timothy (1993). ''At War in the Shadow of Vietnam: U.S. Military Aid to the Royal Lao Government 1955\u20131975''. {{ISBN|9780231079778}}.\n* Conboy, Kenneth and James Morrison (1995). ''Shadow War: The CIA's Secret War in Laos''. Paladin Press. {{ISBN|978-1-58160-535-8}}.\n* Gillespie, Robert M. (2011). ''Black Ops, Vietnam: The Operational History of MACVSOG''. Naval Institute Press. {{ISBN|978-1591143215}}.\n* Guardia, Mike (2011). ''SHADOW COMMANDER: The Epic Story of Donald D. Blackburn-Guerrilla Leader and Special Forces Hero''. Casemate. {{ISBN|978-1612000657}}.\n* Hall, Ross (2007). ''The Ranger Book: A History 1634 \u2013 2006''. Booksurge. {{ISBN|978-1419665745}}.\n\n[[Category:Laotian Civil War]]\n[[Category:1959 in Laos]]\n[[Category:1960 in Laos]]\n[[Category:1961 in Laos]]\n[[Category:Laos\u2013United States relations]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|text=the later rescue mission into Iran to save EDS employees, [[Operation HOTFOOT]]}}\n{{Infobox military operation\n |name          = Project Hotfoot\n |partof        = [[Laotian Civil War]], [[Vietnam War]], and the [[Cold War (1953\u20131962)#Indochina|Cold War in Indochina]]\n |type          = Military training mission\n |location      = [[Kingdom of Laos]]\n |planned_by    = John Heintges, [[United States Indo-Pacific Command#History|CINCPAC]]\n |commanded_by  = [[Donald Blackburn]], [[Arthur D. Simons]], Andrew Jackson Boyle\n |objective     = Train soldiers in the [[Royal Lao Army]], cooperate with French military training teams\n |date          = {{start date|1959|01|22|df=y}}\u2014{{End date|1961|19|04}}\n |executed_by   = [[United States Army Special Forces]] Mobile Training Teams, US control team, French training teams\n |outcome       = Multiple units trained; project develops into [[Operation White Star]]; [[Kong Le]] prepares to lead a [[1960 Laotian coups#Kong Le's coup|military coup against the Kingdom of Laos]]\n |fatalities    = 5\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Laotian Civil War}}\n\n'''Project Hotfoot''' (also known as Operation Hotfoot, originally known as Operation Ambidextrous<ref>Annie Jacobsen, \"Surprise, Kill, Vanish: The Secret History of CIA Paramilitary Armies, Operators, and Assassins,\" (New York: Little, Brown and Company, 2019), p. 112</ref> ) was a secretive military training mission from the United States in support of the [[Kingdom of Laos]]. It ran from 22 January 1959 through 19 April 1961. Working in civilian clothing in conjunction with a French military mission, it concentrated on technical training of the [[Royal Lao Army]].\n\n==Background==\n\nIn March 1945, in the waning days of World War II, the Japanese occupiers of the [[Kingdom of Laos]] forced Lao independence from France. However, the French reasserted themselves in [[French Indochina]] after war's end. During the ensuing [[First Indochina War]], the [[Vietminh|Vietnamese Communist revolutionists]] invaded Laos in March 1953. After occupying large portions of [[Phongsaly]], [[Houaphanh Province]], and mountainous terrain that would become the [[Ho Chi Minh Trail]], the Vietminh moved south to the [[Plain of Jars]] and in a column menacing [[Luang Prabang]]. The Plain of Jars offered the French forces the advantages of attacking the Viet Minh in the open with artillery and air strikes; that assault was halted. The column near Luang Prabang was also stopped when it was ambushed. A third Vietminh force captured [[Thakhek]] on 25 December 1953, cutting Laos in two. This force would not be evicted until February 1954.<ref>Anthony, Sexton, p. 8.</ref>\n\nAs France departed Laos after losing the First Indochina War, the United States moved in to support the [[Royal Lao Government]]. In the wake of the [[1954 Geneva Conference]] and its treaties, the U.S. embassy in [[Vientiane]] established the [[Programs Evaluation Office]] to oversee military aid to Laos. It was established on 13 December 1954. Purportedly staffed by civilians, its personnel were U.S. military retirees, veterans, and reservists. Because the PEO personnel were not serving on active military duty, they were not in violation of the terms of the Geneva treaty.<ref>Castle, pp. 7\u201317.</ref>\n\n==The Heintges Plan==\n\nIn September 1958, Brigadier General [[John Heintges]] left the U.S. Army. In November, he flew to Laos to evaluate the Programs Evaluation Office, with a mandate to take charge of it. Heintges concluded that the staff of the PEO was too small, and seemed intent only on delivering equipment. There was a suspicion that some military aid to Laos was diverted for French use in the [[Algerian War]].<ref name=conboy20>Conboy, Morrison, p. 20.</ref>\n\nReturning to Washington, DC, Heintges lobbied for a larger PEO. He pointed to the sad shape of the [[Royal Lao Army]] as proof of need of U.S. military materiel and training. He was granted an increase in staff. Also, on 22 January 1959, [[CINCPAC]] levied a requirement for 12 [[Special Forces (United States Army)|Special Forces]] Mobile Training Teams of eight men each; they were slated to start six months temporary duty in Laos on 1 April.<ref name=conboy20/>  The operation was kept secret from the American public and, in fact, U.S. commandos that were sent to Laos were given written orders stating they were going to Vietnam.<ref>Annie Jacobsen, \"Surprise, Kill, Vanish: The Secret History of CIA Paramilitary Armies, Operators, and Assassins,\" (New York: Little, Brown and Company, 2019), p. 112</ref> A cover story was arranged; the U.S. mission was purportedly from the [[U.S. National Geodetic Survey]].<ref name=guardia155/> U.S. commandos were disguised as [[civilian]]s and carried civilian identifications.<ref>Annie Jacobsen, \"Surprise, Kill, Vanish: The Secret History of CIA Paramilitary Armies, Operators, and Assassins,\" (New York: Little, Brown and Company, 2019), p. 113</ref> General [[Donald Blackburn]] was charged with command of the mission. He prepared his men by requiring tutoring in both French and Lao, and insisting that all hands read the nonfiction book ''[[Street Without Joy]]'', as well as the novel ''[[The Ugly American]]'', before departure.<ref name=guardia155>Guardia, pp. 155\u2013156.</ref><ref>Gillespie, p. 50.</ref>\n\nHowever, negotiations with the French government delayed things. It was finally decided that the French instructors in Laos under the Geneva treaty would continue to teach tactics, while the American trainers would teach technical subjects. On 24 July 1959, the Mobile Training Teams arrived in [[Vientiane]]. Augmented by a control team 11 strong, the force was dubbed Project Hotfoot (Operation Hotfoot for security purposes); it was also known by the official but little-used title of the Laos Training Advisory Group. They were to work for the PEO as a training arm, teaching Lao soldiers the use of the [[M1 Garand]], [[Browning Automatic Rifle]], [[M1 Carbine]], [[bazooka]], [[M18 recoilless rifle]], and both 60mm and 81mm [[Mortar (weapon)|mortars]]. The Green Berets were commanded on site by Lieutenant Colonel [[Arthur D. Simons]].<ref>Conboy, Morrison, pp. 20\u201321.</ref>\n\n==Hotfoot at work==\n\nHaving been delayed in arrival, the Hotfoot contingent now found itself balked by Lao internal politics. While waiting for the local political situation to clear, the Hotfoot specialists hunkered in training centers at [[Luang Prabang]], [[Savannakhet]], [[Pakse]], and Vientiane. They surveyed the Royal Lao Army as they waited. By the time they were free to begin training at the beginning of September 1959, they had an excellent idea of the retraining task before them. Nine of the Mobile Training Teams were matched with French training teams at regional training camps. Three teams were assigned to build a new training facility northeast of Vientiane on Route 13 at Kilometer 22. This center would be an all-Hotfoot operation, with no French involved. Nearby, at Kilometer 17, they built a ranger training center.<ref>Conboy, Morrison, pp. 23\u201324.</ref>\n\nOn 25 November 1959, one of the Green Beret teams moved from Savannakhet into Military Region 2. They co-located at Khang Khay with a French training team and began building a clinic, rifle range, and demolitions practice area. As 1960 began, training of both regular and [[irregular military]] troops began. The latter were [[Auto Defense Choc]] guerrillas.<ref>Conboy, Morrison, p. 24.</ref>\n\nThe original Hotfoot contingent rotated out of Laos in February 1960, to be replaced by Hotfoot II. The new crew began ranger training for the RLA's ''1 Bataillon Parachutistes'' (1st Paratroop Battalion) and ''2 Bataillon Parachutistes'' (2d Paratroop Battalion). As Hotfoot II left Laos on 29 June 1960, to be replaced by Hotfoot III, 2nd BP began erecting a new battalion encampment for itself at KM 22. On 9 August, the 2nd BP commander, [[Kong Le]], would stage [[1960 Laotian coups#Kong Le's coup|his coup]] from there, commanding his loyal paratroopers.<ref>Conboy, Morrison, pp. 31\u201332.</ref>\n\n==Hotfoot becomes White Star==\n\nUnder incoming American President [[John F. Kennedy]], Hotfoot was rapidly expanded. Andrew Jackson Boyle had just been appointed as chief of the PEO; on 31 January 1961, just after the 19 January [[inauguration]], he requested nine more training teams. His rationale was that every existing or forming battalion in the Royal Lao Army should have an American advisor. The Pentagon signed off on the request, with three packets each consisting of three teams staggering their arrivals in Laos from March through May 1961. The Operation Hotfoot moniker changed to Operation Monkhood.<ref>Conboy, Morrison, p. 50.</ref>\n\nOn 19 April 1961, President Kennedy made a symbolic gesture in allowing the PEO to publicly become a MAAG; PEO members were allowed to don uniforms and resume usual public military courtesies. At the same time, the Hotfoot V teams were also renamed as [[Operation White Star]]. Operation Hotfoot had suffered five killed in action during its duties.<ref>Conboy, Morrison, p. 53.</ref><ref>Hall, pp. 331\u2013332.</ref> When Lieutenant Colonel Simons later organized the [[Operation Ivory Coast|Raid on Son Tay]], he would call upon men who served with him in Laos, such as [[Richard Meadows]] and [[Elliott P. Sydnor, Jr.]].<ref>Hall, pp. 411\u2013413.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n\n* Anthony, Victor B. and Richard R. Sexton (1993). ''The War in Northern Laos''. Command for Air Force History. OCLC 232549943.\n* Castle, Timothy (1993). ''At War in the Shadow of Vietnam: U.S. Military Aid to the Royal Lao Government 1955\u20131975''. {{ISBN|9780231079778}}.\n* Conboy, Kenneth and James Morrison (1995). ''Shadow War: The CIA's Secret War in Laos''. Paladin Press. {{ISBN|978-1-58160-535-8}}.\n* Gillespie, Robert M. (2011). ''Black Ops, Vietnam: The Operational History of MACVSOG''. Naval Institute Press. {{ISBN|978-1591143215}}.\n* Guardia, Mike (2011). ''SHADOW COMMANDER: The Epic Story of Donald D. Blackburn-Guerrilla Leader and Special Forces Hero''. Casemate. {{ISBN|978-1612000657}}.\n* Hall, Ross (2007). ''The Ranger Book: A History 1634 \u2013 2006''. Booksurge. {{ISBN|978-1419665745}}.\n\n[[Category:Laotian Civil War]]\n[[Category:1959 in Laos]]\n[[Category:1960 in Laos]]\n[[Category:1961 in Laos]]\n[[Category:Laos\u2013United States relations]]\n", "name_user": "Mztourist", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe Heintges Plan", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Project_Hotfoot_(Laos)"}
